A Republican Strategy to Counter Obama’s Re-election
The leaders of the Republicans justify their policies with the need to combat electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter to be a myth, affirming that election fraud in the United States is rarer than the number of people killed by lightning strike.
In fact, Republicans’ lawyers have registered only 300 cases of election fraud in the U.S. in 10 years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, these measures partly undermine the democratic system of the United States.
Unlike Canada, the U.S. is responsible for holding elections in individual states.
In this sense, the majority of American governments have since 2009 announced new laws that make the process of registration or balloting more difficult.
This phenomenon gained importance after the November 2010 elections, in which 675 new Republican representatives were registered in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills were introduced in 2011 alone, restricting the exercise of the right to vote in 41 states.
The new election laws require voters to present a photo ID and proof of U.S. citizenship.
In addition, these laws also shorten the periods for early voting, declare the right to register as a voter on election day invalid, and deny citizens the right to vote for which a judicial act exists.
Prior to the 2006 elections, no U.S. state required voters to show a photo ID.
Indiana was the first state to make such a claim.
In 2008, the Supreme Court of the United States upheld the constitutionality of the Indiana law.
The Republican authorities hastened to extend this practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they have promoted bills in 34 states that force voters to show a photo ID.
It is important to note that unlike Quebec, U.S. citizens do not have a universal ID card such as the health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of U.S. citizens, or 21 million eligible voters, do not have a government-issued photo ID.
In addition, five million new voters did not have such an identity card in 2012.
However, often more than a hundred dollars are to be paid to obtain the required ID.
Young people, minorities and people with low incomes are disproportionately affected by the new restrictions.
In fact, 25% of African Americans, 15% of people with an income of less than $35,000, 18% of citizens over 65, and 20% of voters between the ages of 18 and 29 do not have the required photo ID.
This goes even further.
Students who are seen as voters who increasingly vote for democratic candidates are not allowed to use their photo ID issued by their institution in several states.
On the other hand, the same states allow members of fishing or hunting clubs who vote more strongly for the Republican side to use the cards issued by these clubs for elections.
Prior to 2004, no state required proof of citizenship to vote.
Arizona was the first state to make such a claim.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove their U.S. citizenship.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting Hispanic votes.
Because it is obvious that two out of three Hispanic voters prefer the Democratic Party.
In addition, Republican lawmakers in 2011 promoted laws in eight states that abolished voter registration on Election Day.
In addition, you have restricted the right of individuals and groups to provide assistance to those voters who wish to register.
These restrictions are not without consequences.
For example, the campaigns for voter registration in the 2004 general election have helped to register about 10 million citizens.
As a result of the measures adopted since 2009, the share of new voters registered in 2010 has decreased by 17% compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers in five other states have passed laws aimed at shortening the period for early voting.
For example, in the 2008 Florida general election, 33% of the voters who voted in advance were African-Americans, although they made up only 13% of the state’s voters.
The same applies to the Hispanic population.
The latter accounted for only 11% of voters, but 24% of citizens who voted in advance.
In contrast, the Whites, who made up 76% of the electorate, made up only 46% of the voters who elected in advance.
Of course, the democratic legislators and their supporters have vigorously opposed the passing of laws restricting voter registration.
Several bills have been blocked by the vetoes of democratic governors.
The Attorney General of the United States has intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
They were able to partially limit the damage.
For example, only 16 of the 34 states have laws requiring the display of a photo ID.
However, the new rules introduced in 2012 will undoubtedly make it more difficult to exercise the right to vote.
The democratic critics denounce the party-political nature of the adopted laws and see in them as a clear goal the influence of the results in the states that are decisive for 2012.
A 2011 report by the Brennan Center shows that those states that passed these laws make up 171 of the 270 votes required in the Electoral College to win the presidency.
It is too early to confirm with certainty that these changes to the electoral system legislation will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential elections.
But one thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, these measures partly undermine the democratic system of the United States.
Early detection of prostate cancer: should the test be done or not?
In fact, the PSA test sometimes shows erroneous results, with false negative or false positive results, which lead to unnecessary medical interventions.
This leads to greater hesitation of the already undecided men for carrying out early detection tests.
Should the test be done or not?
We have obtained the opinion of two specialists.
In the US studies, there were numerous interference factors between the control groups, making it difficult to interpret these data and make clear recommendations.
Another study, this time from Europe, concluded that there is a difference in the mortality of patients with and without early detection.
This study has also shown that when followed up after 12 years, the likelihood of metastasis formation is 30 to 40% higher if no early detection has been performed.
Therefore, I recommend the test from the age of 50 years or 40 years, if you have a direct relative who was already suffering from prostate cancer.
Men of African American ancestry also have a higher risk.
The most important thing is to make the right decision as soon as a cancer has been detected.
There are cancers that are aggressive and others that are indolent.
The patient must really understand the extent of the risk of his cancer disease by showing him the possible options in which prostate cancer can remain untreated if he does not affect the quality of life in the long term, and in these cases it is rather decided to actively monitor the disease.
Today, many men who have been diagnosed with cancer do not receive treatment because their cancer is not aggressive and does not pose a threat to their lives.
Active monitoring is suggested and treatment is offered as the disease progresses.
The criteria for deciding who should be treated and who should not are determined with increasing accuracy.
Therefore, I recommend that the test be carried out.
However, the most important thing is to talk to your doctor to determine if it should be done or not.
In collaboration with the International Society of Urology, Movember has developed an instrument that makes it possible to evaluate the pros and cons of PSA testing.
