Prevention of the disease
Unfortunately, there is no miracle cure for cancer.
Despite advances in research, adopting a healthy lifestyle remains the best way to reduce the risk of getting sick from it.
It is estimated that 30% of cancers could be prevented if everyone ate well and moved sufficiently.
"If there were no more smokers, this value would increase to at least 50%," said André Beaulieu, a spokesman for the Canadian Cancer Society.
However, it is assumed that about 10% of cancers are caused by inheritance.
Many of them remain completely unsolved.
For the Canadian cancer society, the fight against tobacco addiction remains a priority, despite the decline in the number of smokers.
Smoking is responsible for 85% of lung cancer cases.
It is also a risk factor for several other cancers.
It greatly harms people's health.
"There are still 1.5 million smokers in Quebec today," said spokesman André Beaulieu.
10 years after quitting smoking, the risk of dying from cancer is reduced by half.
The weight
According to the Canadian Cancer Society, overweight and obesity also promote the onset of the disease.
They appear to increase the risk of breast, uterine, colon, esophageal, pancreatic and uterine cancers.
“Research shows that regular physical activity throughout life protects against colorectal cancer,” he adds.
The nutrition
The organization also recommends limiting the consumption of red meat.
Too much of it increases the risk of developing colorectal cancer or colon cancer.
Sausages should also be avoided.
The preservation of meat by smoking, drying or salting can lead to the formation of carcinogens.
"The latter can damage the body's cells and lead to the development of cancer," he explains.
Vitamins
In recent years, several scientists have investigated the relationship between vitamin supplements and cancer.
However, their investigations are not conclusive at this time.
According to the Canadian Cancer Society, studies on vitamin E are contradictory.
While one study found a reduction in the risk of prostate cancer, another showed a more likely increase.
The effect of vitamin D on cancer has also not yet been clearly demonstrated.
In addition, Mr. Beaulieu stresses the importance of talking to his doctor about his concerns and his family predicament.
"Performing an early detection test does not lead to cancer."
The Higgs boson
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson has sparked some excitement over the past summer, and for good reason.
In fact, it is believed that this boson is involved in nothing less than the mechanism responsible for the mass of all objects in the universe.
And finally, it is the last particle whose existence has been predicted by the standard model - our best or "least false" explanation of nature and the behavior of matter - but has not yet been empirically observed.
But for physicists, it’s not entirely certain yet that it’s really the Higgs.
We know without a shadow of a doubt that we have a real new particle, and that it closely resembles the Higgs boson predicted by the standard model.
In addition, this seems to be confirmed by new data presented this week at a major physics congress in Kyoto, but data is still missing to be completely sure.
Still, let’s assume that it’s actually the Higgs, as there seems to be only a small risk of being deceived, and let’s look at what it’s all about.
There is a law in this world that is inevitable, which means that two objects cannot exist in the same place at the same time.
It is not possible to violate this rule - and do not try it too hard, as you will get hurt.
For even if particle physics is a really strange world, it turns out that such a law also applies to them: the Pauli exclusion principle, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time when they are in the same "quantum state", with this "state" consisting largely of some of their properties.
Based on this, the physicists divide the particles into two categories.
In a corner are the good citizens, who are called Fermione and obedient to the Pauli principle.
And in the other, the bosons move, a bad band of anarchists, to whom nothing is sacred – certainly not this principle, which means that they can in fact be in the same place at the same time.
According to The Particle Adventure, these bosons are divided into two groups: the mesons we are not going to treat here and the "force particles" through which the great forces of nature spread and with which the Higgs boson would somehow be related.
But it must be emphasized here that these bosons are not all as exotic creatures as you might think.
If you are able to read this chronicle, then only thanks to a boson of extraordinary banality: the photon or the "particle of light" which is the "bot" of electromagnetic force.
When a particle accelerates with an electric charge or changes direction, the electromagnetic field is “disturbed” at exactly this location, much like a pebble thrown into a pond.
This "disruption" produces an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.), and this wave is nothing but a photon and thus one of the bosons "carriers of force".
Stable field
The same applies to the Higgs boson, with the difference that another field, the Higgs field, must be "disturbed" in order for this boson to manifest itself.
However, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field; the exciter must reach very high energies, a little like a frozen pond, the surface of which could only be disturbed by a very large rock.
That's why a huge particle accelerator like CERN is required - the Large Hadron Collider is a ring with a circumference of 27 km! - to achieve such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is once again helpful in explaining the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
In fact, not all particles and not all materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do this, but others don’t — for example, a sheet of paper would never keep itself on the refrigerator.
And equally, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those who do have a mass, while the others (like the photon, by the way) do not.
For what can all this research be "good", asks Mrs Plamondon?
For science, they serve to review the Standard Model (SM), and they also allow physicists to accurately examine any deviations between the observations and predictions of the SM.
By the way, there are numerous physicists who hope that such deviations will be found, since the slightest difference could open a door to a "new physics" and plug some holes in the model.
It has to be said that the latter still has major flaws, as it offers no explanation for the gravity (ups!) and dark matter that makes up about 80% of the matter of the universe (again ups!).
However, no such deviations have been found at CERN so far.
Impact
The impact of this research on the general population is more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there would be none.
By the way: in the early 60s, the pioneers of lasers in Bell laboratories did not suspect that their work would trigger such a revolution.
They saw scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, the late physicist Willard Boyle – who worked in the Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in the 1960s, and who himself developed the first permanent tri-laser (the first were pulsed) in 1962 – has already told us that the laser was initially considered more of a “laboratory toy”.
Just imagine...
In addition, applications can also arise from all the instruments that surround the research.
Willard Boyle, for example, developed a small light sensor in 1969 during his work in optics.
Although it was not the original purpose, this sensor now serves all digital cameras worldwide as an "eye" and brought him the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2009.
Of course, this does not mean that the activities of the LHC will necessarily change our lives, but it does mean that you really can never know...
Palliative care - the best way to die... <0x7C> Le Devoir
With its committee on "Death in Dignity", Quebec recently discussed the delicate issue of the end of life.
The debate must be resumed soon, although a draft law is being prepared.
However, much remains to be done in this important area.
Le Devoir has tried to take a closer look at this.
A few weeks ago, Mr. L. lived alone in his apartment in the Montérégie.
The prostate cancer that consumed him had left him with a period of two years.
"They gave me five years to live, I managed seven years," he said half-heartedly, lying in his bed in Victor-Gadbois's palliative care home in Beloeil, where he had arrived the day before.
“However, it’s always a shock, you can’t be prepared for it,” he says.
The disease does its job: an immeasurable weakness prevents him from going to the toilet alone and even eating himself.
Sitting at the table before a delicious lunch, he reluctantly agrees to let himself be helped with food.
Courageously, he even manages to smile and talk to the strangers who are busy around him, bring him his medicines, and offer him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
“My biggest wish is to have my diarrhea cured, as this is humiliating,” he says.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for this evil.
“Over the course of our lives, we learn that a man is peeing while standing,” says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at Victor-Gadbois’s home.
Returning to childhood is an unacceptable humiliation for some people.
“It depends on the person’s ability to take a step back,” he notes.
Because according to several people who work in palliative care, major events take place in the midst of these setbacks.
Patients who are admitted to the Victor-Gadbois Palliative Care Home are all suffering from cancer.
They have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
At this stage, they are no longer overcrowded with so-called "healing" care by the doctors and nurses who care for them.
For Ms. A., 89 years old, the worst fear is to die “consciously and by suffocation.”
But through the illness, I really got to know my children.
“I have good children,” she adds.
“I don’t have any more wishes in life,” she says, before accepting that you’re putting on a mask to help her breathe.
In the next few days, however, she expects one last visit from her son, who is from Italy.
In the Victor-Gadbois home, you can offer a group of volunteers personal care and assistance with food intake.
Palliative care is used when there are no other options.
To make dying more enjoyable.
In Quebec, there is a palliative care bed for 11,700 people.
This is very little considering that one day we will all die.
Here, life is continued under the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors of the home.
Both at the level of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
The dying person is given a mouth care with brandy or Pepsi as desired.
Diabetics no longer need to control their blood sugar levels.
And death is part of everyday life.
Last night we served Mr. X a beer that died during the night.
This morning his son will drink the beer at the feet of the deceased.
“We are helping families and patients alike,” says Nathalie Savard, director of care.
In the home of Victor-Gadbois, there is no day like the other.
In addition to a 93-year-old man who enjoys the last family reunion in the yard and is well supported by his pillows as one approaches his honor, a 36-year-old man surrounded by his parents, his wife, and his two young children dies tragically after trying everything to survive.
“For six months, three to five beds have always been occupied with cancer patients under the age of 45,” says Dr. Christiane Martel.
53% of patients admitted to Victor-Gadbois’ home come from their place of residence, 47% come from the hospital.
Problem of access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, i.e., care intended to alleviate the suffering of patients who have reached the final stage of their lives, whether at home, in the hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the Victor-Gadbois home and the Greater Montreal Home Palliative Care Society, specialize more or less exclusively in the care of cancer patients.
Precisely this great inadequacy in health care in Quebec ensures that several doctors specialized in palliative care face the adoption of a law to regulate euthanasia and assisted suicide with concerns.
Since October, a manifesto has been in circulation, signed by prominent palliative care personalities such as Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, to express their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, Quebec’s health care system is not powerful enough to ensure that everyone has the right to quality palliative care before being accepted to transition to euthanasia.
Recently, she says, I saw a patient who had been in the emergency room for 14 days with great pain, without any measures being taken to relieve her.
I fear that patients only want to die because they do not receive adequate health care.
And at the same time, several oncologists treat their patients with bites until the last day, despite the worst prognosis.
Hél<0xC3><0xA8>ne Richard’s chances of survival were already minimal when she discontinued a difficult chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was going to stop the treatment, she told me that she regretted giving up the fight, she told me.
She told me that I was at the end!
No omnipotent care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who have been asked to die thank the nursing staff for not allowing this desire after their pain has been alleviated by a palliative care team.
However, it must be clearly said that palliative care is not omnipotent in the treatment of pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, head of palliative care at the Greater Montreal Society of Home Palliative Care, 8% of patients do not respond to pain treatment.
At the very end of life, doctors often resort to terminal sedation, which results in either sporadically or permanently putting the patient to sleep until the time of his death.
We can no longer act as if we do not perceive this side of suffering.
Patients without pain relief will increasingly have the opportunity to resort to this terminal sedation.
Patients whose pain is not relieved all say the same sentence: "I want to die."
But that doesn’t necessarily mean, “I want you to put me to sleep,” but, “I want my pain to be relieved.”
