A few thousand websites accept Bitcoin as a donation or as a means of payment.
After Bitcoin’s price peaked at $30 (<0xE2><0x82><0xAC>23) in June 2011, it fell to $2 five months later before recovering to around $10 today (the prices are listed on bitcoincharts.com).
Nothing particularly impressive compared to the world trade of real currencies or financial products.
Nevertheless, the European Central Bank (ECB) has shown interest in this in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
It describes Bitcoin as "the virtual currency with the greatest success", "in competition with the dollar or euro" and "similar to conventional currencies".
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual currencies such as the “credits” that are used to advance in a video game that you can win or buy (and sometimes even trade back) by playing.
The social network Facebook has also developed such a system.
However, trade is controlled and processed each time by a central authority.
With Bitcoin, all network nodes are simultaneously custodians of the ledger, auditors, money issuers as well as buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Every transaction between two users actually takes place between two email addresses in the form of an email.
With the difference that the user can choose a different address for each payment, which ensures anonymity.
A number of the data associated with this transaction is electronically signed by a double encryption system.
In this way, the network can verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Using the contents of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the traded Bitcoins are present in the public accounts’ ledger distributed throughout the network.
The crucial step is to include this new transaction in this book.
This is done via a mathematical task that is started on the computers, with the winner, who is a kind of provisional central banker, having the privilege of adding this additional line.
It is a fragmentation of the file, i.e. the conversion of a large file into a shorter and clearer electronic fingerprint.
The computers "take" the new transaction and add a number to it before the whole thing is "hacked".
The goal is to find the number that produces a special fingerprint (many zeros at the beginning).
If this number is found, the other nodes can easily check if it is the correct one.
The transaction is thus permanently linked to the chain of all other transactions, and any modification would change the fingerprint.
If a user wants to pay for fraud twice very quickly (less than 10 minutes) with the same money, only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network and the other would remain unlinked as both have different fingerprints.
The computer that has solved the task will receive 50 Bitcoins.
To prevent inflation, this reward is regularly halved, probably before the end of 2012.
The Bitcoins in circulation are thus limited to 21 million, but can be divided up to a hundred million, which leaves a certain margin...
In addition, the difficulty of the task is increased with each improvement in computing performance.
The life of the network has already had ups and downs.
The websites that provide services for Bitcoin were attacked and the Bitcoin deposits were stolen.
“The vulnerability used does not affect the actual protocol,” assures Pierre Noizat, who has just introduced Paymium, which is a real money payment company using the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also reports on the possibilities of money laundering using this anonymous service.
However, cash also has these shortcomings.
Important actors such as Wikipedia refuse donations of this kind.
They are accepted by others, such as the WordPress blog platform.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron from the Weizmann Institute in Israel analyzed the ledger and showed that almost 80% of Bitcoins are not in circulation.
In November, a "mega-final sale" was launched.
“Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged,” says Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, the company that converts Bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, who is also the author of a book on this currency, firmly believes in the potential of this technology as a transactional network.
Its Paytunia system corresponds to a credit card (with real money) or a contactless payment with a mobile phone, but uses Bitcoin to validate the transactions that are cheaper as a result.
In addition, the owner manages his identity and can therefore remain anonymous.
The system can be easily implemented by the merchants, and the latter do not need to install new terminals or computer programs.
You just need to specify an address that can be “photographed and recognized” by a phone, Pierre Noizat says, assuring that he has thousands of users.
There is a general trend in which hierarchical systems are considered in favour of more horizontally oriented systems.
“It will take some time for Bitcoin to get through, but 2013 could be a turning point,” he predicts.
By the way, the ECB’s report envisages reassessing the various risks that are now considered high in the event of the success of this currency.
We've moved out of Afghanistan.
And after that?
French troops have left their responsibilities in Afghanistan (Kapisa and Surobi).
NATO and the United States are expected to follow at the end of 2014.
It is time for the Afghan army to regain possession of its territory, and for the Afghan people to decide their future without expecting anything from us.
In particular, we have punished the Afghan farmers by treating them as terrorists.
And ourselves with our 88 soldiers killed, as well as the wounded and wounded.
The Taliban are made up of foreign extremists, former leaders who have fled to Pakistan, but often also farmers who deny an armed foreign presence, as at the time of the Soviets.
They want to defend their centuries-old and archaic traditions, even if they are joined by jihadists, Pakistanis, Arabs, Uzbeks and Tajiks.
Tolerated, sometimes supported by local insurgents, the latter will no longer be there when Western countries become more discreet.
The withdrawal of the French troops from the base in Nijrab, which I observed from a hill planted with almond trees, which was financed by French loans, was duly carried out.
The convoys of trucks and tanks flown by helicopters reached Kabul without being attacked.
As of the end of 2014, there will be no more Taliban inflows into Kabul.
Since their irresistible advance from 1994 to 1996, the conditions have changed.
At that time, Kabul was empty and the country was overwhelmed by war due to the fighting of the various rebel groups.
Their takeover was then seen as a kind of liberation and return to security.
Afghan women have paid the price for the obscurantism of the farmers overwhelmed by the Al-Qaeda organization, but their situation has not improved to this day.
Former Mujahideen, the Afghan government and the current Taliban have a common desire to keep women in a subordinate position.
The main figures of the anti-Soviet war came back to power in 2001.
They have turned into businessmen by confiscating government land to sell as construction land to refugees from Iran and Pakistan, thus benefiting from massive American subcontracting.
They were in disrepute, and most of them were not themselves involved in the fighting.
As I have heard in the campaigns, the people want a government that is not made up of thieves.
Many young people want to leave the country, just like those who were able to take advantage of American subsidies: the capital flight is considerable.
The young people are fed up with the war and its ideologies.
During their exile in Iran or Pakistan, they have had contact with the modern world, and have enjoyed its benefits.
About 65% of the population is under the age of 25; Kabul now has 5 million inhabitants, which is one-fifth of the total population.
In the cities, state schools are full of girls and boys.
These young people, who do not want to return to the obscurantism of the former parties or to the corruption of certain leaders, will have to be provided with jobs.
Everyone, including the armed parties, is obsessed with mobile phones; the TV with its Turkish series, which represent a modern world, is watched everywhere.
There is an army now.
Will the authorities under whose command she will be standing be considered legitimate?
Former commanders of the anti-Soviet struggle are already trying to restore the militias in the province, which will escape the power of the central government.
Afghanistan, the land of mountains with strong local identities, should have benefited from a certain decentralization like the Western nations, but by abolishing the office of Prime Minister, which had existed since the 1964 constitution, the US wanted to make it a centralized state with a strong presidential power.
President Karzai does not want foreign controls, especially on the occasion of the elections scheduled for April 2014.
However, his country has been dependent on foreign aid since the 1950s and long before that.
Industries have not been rebuilt, functional dams are not present and important irrigation systems have not been repaired.
Everything is imported; apart from fruits and vegetables, nothing is produced.
The private initiative is given priority.
In a country that has been ravaged by 30 years of war, state control of infrastructure would have been required.
Rumors have been spread that Afghanistan has immense land resources.
This further reinforces the impression that the Western countries were only on the ground to seize it.
No mining is possible without energy to process the iron or copper ore on site, or without means of transport for export over the mountains.
The Chinese have already almost left the Mes Aynak copper mine, let the international archaeologists (funded by the World Bank) make their excavations at the huge Buddhist site and remain the main employers of the province.
One day it will also be necessary for Afghanistan and Pakistan, on which imports and exports are largely dependent, to resume normal relations.
The withdrawal of the French combat troops was completed on 20 November.
The new cooperation agreement provides for the continuation of traditional aid: girls’ and boys’ high schools, the French Institute at universities, the French Institute, cooperation in the military, legal, medical and agricultural fields, support for the archaeological delegation.
Since 2009, a service of "civil-military actions" of the Ministry of Defense (Cimic), which was suspended in 2012, has carried out numerous non-profit works and measures for the rehabilitation of agriculture in dozens of mountain villages, and has been carried out by a small French non-governmental organization to try to gain the "hearts and minds open to help".
These works, which required numerous local workers, have helped to suppress the uprising: irrigation, wells, drinking water, reforestation, fruit trees, soil protection and increased agricultural land use.
Which souvenir do we leave behind after military spending of two billion euros?
A much more modest budget will help improve local living conditions, which are often very harsh in these valleys at an altitude of more than 2,000 meters.
The embassy has received dozens of written requests for small agricultural projects from municipalities in the province of Kapisa.
In order for farmers to get rid of the insurgency led by foreign groups, which they claim is their wish, the continuation of small, well-controlled and directly related civil aid would be necessary in their favour.
A Constitution with the Breaking Rod in Egypt
This is a new poker game from President Mohammed Mursi.
While Egypt remains divided more than ever about the constitutional declaration that gives it unlimited power of attorney, it has decided to put everything on a map.
To everyone’s surprise, he announced on Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would adopt its final version the next day.
Just a week ago, the Head of State had granted this plenary two additional months for the completion of its work.
Egypt has now relied for almost two years on a provisional, multiple-changed text, weakening institutional stability and leading to legal confusion.
This new initiative has only ensured an even stronger division of the country.
For his opponents, the president remains in his "autocratic delirium" by continuing to "break his word" and "step the law with his feet".
On the side of his supporters, he assures that it is a way to end the institutional and political crisis as quickly as possible and to speed up the transition process.
A referendum should be held within 14 days.
A very short period of time, forcing the brothers to forgo their plan to explain the text section by section to the Egyptians.
For the president, it’s also a way to regain his public and democratic legitimacy as the protest rages across the country.
After confirming in an interview with the American weekly show Time, Mohammed Morsi seems to be convinced that the Egyptians will vote benevolently.
When an ultimatum is put to the Egyptian people with this recourse to a hasty vote: "Either you vote for my draft or I retain unlimited power", the latter should supposedly end after the adoption of the Constitution.
85 mostly Islamist members of this Constituent Assembly passed the text yesterday in a strange atmosphere.
The majority of the Liberals have not complied with the request.
Shortly before the constitutional declaration in mid-November, they turned away because they felt they had not been able to put their views into practice.
Representatives of human rights organizations, religious minorities or civil society have acted in the same way.
In order to reach the decision-making power, 11 people, deputy members, were added yesterday morning in a hurry.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
It is not surprising that the articles were usually adopted unanimously.
The commentators, by the way, found it amusing that the only disagreement of the day... was expressed at the time of prayer, as some members of the panel felt that the pendulum clock of the Constituent Assembly did not go exactly.
The text, which was adopted last night, consists of 234 articles.
Article 2, which drew all attention to itself, ultimately remains identical to that of the 1971 Constitution and states that "the principles of sharia are the main source of law".
The Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is an important demand, had the hope of replacing "the principles" with "the rules", which would have made a stricter application possible.
For the Islamists, the fact that this article has not been changed is proof of their goodwill and respect for the other members of Egyptian society.
"Sacredness" is echoed by the liberals, who see this only as a propaganda attack.
Because according to them, the Islamization of the Constitution takes place over other articles.
In particular, they have in mind Article 220, which confers an advisory function on Al-Azhar University, in particular with regard to the verification of compliance with the laws of Sharia.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, this is worrying, since "the people who are asked to comment have not been elected and do not have any democratic legitimacy.
Here you can see the first signs of a theocracy.”
The fears of the Liberals are also fueled by the fact that the next rector of this university is far less moderate than the current one.
"At the moment, there is no concrete religious commitment to be recognized.
With this constitution we remain within the framework of the bourgeois state.
Most of the lawyers who have worked on this text are not ulema, but academics who have been trained in part in the French system," said Alexis Blouet, who writes a doctoral thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
He admits, however, that "there may be ambiguity with regard to Article 220, since the terms used are borrowed from the religious vocabulary.
It refers in particular to the "Fiqh" [Islamic jurisprudence].
And in the future, the question could be raised as to the extent to which civil judges are competent to decide on this."
In addition to its religious aspect, the text adopted yesterday is heavily criticized for the far-reaching powers it grants to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood argues that these are significantly reduced compared to the former regime.
Another point of contention: the powers of the army.
In accordance with the desire of the military, the examination of the defense budget is not submitted to Parliament, but to a national defense council.
Similarly, there will be no ban on civil proceedings in military courts, as the human rights associations have demanded.
The latter also share their concerns about the text, which they consider to be a threat to freedom.
The actual existence of blasphemy is maintained, and insults are now banned, which could have serious consequences for the right to free expression, especially for the press.
In addition, no longer refers to the protection of women, emphasizes Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
In their opinion, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture by Article 36.
This word was not included in the previous constitution.
While the Egyptian president had to speak on television last night, demonstrations are scheduled for this afternoon.
The supporters of the head of state will march on Saturday.
In Israel, Ukrainian tourists await sacred sites, the navel of the world and a sea of salt
The Promised Land brings together the glory of biblical truths, modern comfort and untouched nature.
AIF gives you the top five reasons to visit Israel.
bowing down before the holy places
Visit the Jordan River where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that all who bathe in this river receive God’s blessing.
Galilee is the place where Jesus performed his miracles: the transformation of water into wine at a wedding feast, walking on the water, the silence of the storm and the catch of fish.
It was here that Jesus appeared to his disciples after the resurrection.
Most of the shrines are in Jerusalem.
Here, believers follow the Way of Suffering or the Way of the Cross of Jesus Christ (in Latin: Via Dolorosa).
The path begins at the Roman fortress of Antonia, Pretorium, where the court was, and leads through the streets of the old town to the tomb church on Mount Golgotha, where the crucifixion site, the anointing stone and the tomb of Jesus are located.
Here, according to the Christian view, is the navel of the world, which symbolizes the salvation of humanity.
The Monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem stands at the place where, according to Christian legend, the tree from which the cross was made for the crucifixion of Jesus grew.
Jerusalem is also home to the holiest site of the Jews - the Wailing Wall, the remains of a temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 AD.
Traditionally, people of different faiths leave notebooks with wishes, which then go into fulfillment.
Take a journey to the heights
The ruins of the fortress of Massada form the remains of the secret hideout from enemies, which Herod the Great had built in 25 AD for his family.
They lie on a rock wall in the mountains at 450 meters above sea level.
Only mountaineers can reach the ruins on their own.
Everyone else brings an aerial cable car to this historic summit.
In the north of the country in 1600 to 2040 meters altitude is the famous ski resort Hermon, where it attracts countless tourists in the winter months.
From the foot of the mountain you can get there by shuttle bus.
The ski slopes have a total length of 45 kilometers.
According to an ancient legend, supposedly pagan gods lived on the top of the mountain.
Visiting Unique Museums
There are almost 300 museums in this country.
With just one trip, not all of them can be visited.
But at least the five most interesting of them should be paid a visit.
One of them is the Israel Museum near the Knesset (Parliament).
There, ancient Qumran manuscripts or scrolls from the Dead Sea, found in rock caves in the Judean Desert, are preserved, as well as about 500 thousand archaeological and anthropological exhibits.
The Museum of Art in Tel Aviv is also worth a visit.
There, the collection of works by the Impressionists and Expressionists Monet, Pissaro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso is exhibited.
In Akko you can visit the museum in Bad Al Basha, which houses several halls of old Turkish baths with sculptures of the visitors and bathers of the time.
In Caesarea you should visit the unique private Ralli Museum, where you can admire sculptures by Dali and Rodin.
There are no museum guides or souvenir shops.
Admission is free, and donations are generally declined.
The fifth museum, the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv, tells of one of the most shocking chapters in history.
The most poignant section is the Children’s Memorial, built to commemorate the 1.5 million children who were destroyed in the concentration camps and gas chambers.
When entering the room, there is total darkness.
The stars sparkle.
And the names of the Jewish children and the countries in which they died are heard.
Ukraine is also mentioned there.
Doing something for health
The three main recreation areas of Israel are located on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
In each of the three places there are swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and oceanariums.
Amazingly, the Red Sea is also bathed in the winter months, as the water temperature there does not fall below 21°C and the air warms up to 23°C.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and is bathed there all year round.
By the way, this unusual sea with a location of 417 meters below sea level is the deepest sea in the world.
Its turquoise water has a high salt content and thus carries even non-swimmers easily on the surface.
The surrounding countryside is indescribably beautiful.
Visitors come here for treatments using salt water (natural salt brine) and healing mud, as well as for treating skin inflammation, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes, and to soothe tired nerves.
Touching the Secrets of Antiquity
This is the secret of Tel Aviv’s old town, the city of Jaffa on the Mediterranean coast.
Through this city passed the famous sea route, which connected Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and ancient Egyptian legends.
According to legend, Noah built his ark right here, and Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda, with whom he led a long and happy life in this place.
Tourists like to stroll through the narrow streets named after the zodiac signs.
Fortuna is supposed to be the legend after all those who touch the walls in the alley with their star sign.
In Jaffa, you can meet newlywed couples from all over Israel and even other countries on photo dates.
In Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can stroll through the Roman theater and conquer the fortress of the Crusaders.
In Roman times, Caesarea was the most important city of Judea and residence of Roman governors, including Pontius Pilate.
In the carefully restored theatre, evening concerts and operas are performed today.
Highlights for tourists
When you go to Israel, don’t worry about your poor English skills: About 30% of Israelis speak Russian.
The money in the trip is better to take with you not in euros, but in dollars that can be easily exchanged in shekels (current exchange rate: 1 dollar to 3.8 shekels).
In the city you can usually get there by bus, but in Jerusalem there is also a high-speed railway and in Haifa the only metro line in the country with six stations that connects the lower city with the upper city.
In fact, it is an underground cable car.
A journey within the city costs 6 shekels regardless of the means of transport, which is enough including transfers for a journey of up to 1.5 hours.
According to Jewish tradition, the Sabbath is celebrated in Israel on Saturday.
From Friday evening to sunset on Saturday, markets and shops are closed, and public transport is at rest.
And on Sunday morning the work week begins.
In many cafes, restaurants and restaurants, only kosher food is served, which excludes pork, seafood, fish without scales and foods that contain both dairy and meat products.
Instead, you have the choice between different dishes with ham and beef, soups and desserts (prepared with coconut milk), traditional Jewish hummus paste, various sauces, fried balls of pureed beans and peas (falafel), as well as fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs in the streets of Israeli cities.
For this, there are many well-nourished cats, who comfortably and unobtrusively stray through the streets.
In the evening you can even see them sleeping on the roofs of parked cars.
The cats like lively places and do not say no to treats.
Depending on the brand, a rental car costs between $37 per day (Hyundai Getz) and $188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80).
The insurance costs an additional $15 per day.
And bike rental costs 15 shekels per day.
Tickets for museums cost an average of 30 shekels.
In numbers
In 2012, more than three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel.
Most adventurers and recreational seekers came from Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England, the USA and Ukraine.
From January to October 2012, 118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists came to the Promised Land, which corresponds to an increase of 51% compared to the comparison period in 2010, before the lifting of the visa requirement on February 9, 2011.
"The big and powerful" leads to Moscow: migrants save money for language
While MPs and civil rights activists are discussing the benefits of the law on mandatory language tests for migrants, criminals are already dealing with fake certificates.
Every year 13 million guest workers come to Moscow, St. Petersburg and other cities of Russia.
Most of them are citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to earn money for the maintenance of the families left in the home.
On December 1st, a law came into force, according to which every migrant worker must take a test that certifies knowledge of the Russian language.
So far, this scheme only applies to migrants who want to work in the services sector, in the municipal housing industry and in the retail sector.
However, the tests will become mandatory for all guest workers over time, according to the Federal Migration Agency.
In doing so, one must not only take language tests, but also take tests into Russian history and the foundations of legislation.
Language skills must be demonstrated both for the receipt and extension of the work permit.
Exceptions apply only to citizens of countries where Russian is the official language.
Also exempt from this law are persons who received their educational certificates and diplomas before the collapse of the USSR in 1991.
Sense, Problematics and Protection of Rights
All the examination centres will be under the auspices of the Pushkin Institute for the Russian Language, the Russian University of Friendship, Moscow State University, St. Petersburg State University and other Russian universities.
The migrants can take the tests in all cities; already more than 160 corresponding centers have been opened in Russia.
The initiative to introduce the tests was supported by the deputies of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Agency.
Civil rights activists, on the other hand, repeatedly asked the following question in the press before the law came into force: What does it actually mean?
What changes does the regulation make in having to show language skills, both for the Russians and for the guest workers?
First of all, the migration authority’s spokesman said, the aim is to reduce the number of forced labourers.
“Many are now talking about protecting the rights of migrant workers,” said Viktor Sebelev, head of the Federal Migration Agency’s office in Tajikistan.
However, your rights must be protected before you leave.
Only an organized recruitment will solve 90% of the problems of foreign workers.
Migrants without a job, education, language skills and medical examination face problems.
Sebelev is convinced that a future migrant without language skills will inevitably meet people with evil intentions, who will put him under the guise of help in a dark, narrow barrack, where he will endure with dozens of unequal months without food and documents and work 12 to 14 hours a day.
We receive many complaints from our migrants.
“At home, you will be promised the One, and on arrival you will be cheated, your passports will be taken away and you will not receive the promised salary,” confirmed Tolib Schwaripov, head of the main administration for labour migration of the Tajik Migration Authority.
Don't scold, boss!
Nevertheless, many citizens of the Central Asian republics, who want to make their money in Russia, admit that they not only do not master the language of the target country, but also can hardly express themselves in writing in their own language.
Of course, this is not so much their fault, but rather the evil: only a few Turkmen, Uzbeks and Tajiks can afford even a reasonable basic education.
Because in their families there is not even money to feed the children, let alone to buy them decent clothes, shoes and school supplies.
As a teenager, these children immediately seize the first opportunity to make money.
"It's difficult without language skills," they admit.
"You feel humiliated and inferior."
Civil rights activists emphasize the following important aspect of the law.
Only immigrants with legal status are required to take the test.
If you do not have this status, then there is no examination and therefore no official work.
Meanwhile, the majority of guest workers remain illegally in Russia.
"Welcome" or "Access for unauthorized persons is prohibited"
Many migrants confirm that it is not easy to obtain official status in Russia.
The reason is bureaucratic hurdles and, of course, the language difficulties.
In addition, the legalization costs money: 12 to 16 thousand rubles.
A fake registration can be done quickly and only for one and a half thousand.
The employees of the Russian police know that our documents are mostly fake and we are not registered, and this then leads to cases of extortion.
"You want one or two hundred rubles for cigarettes and tea," the Tajik Umed Hushkadamov told reporters.
"Don't be afraid of the cost of false papers"
Already on the day the law came into force, it turned out that not only the registration documents of migrants can be falsified.
Some fake certificates certifying the completion of the language test have already been confiscated by employees of the Federal Migration Agency.
The fake papers were printed with an ordinary color printer.
Of course, the new owners did not receive these for free: every migrant who hoped to be able to save himself from the tests, paid seven thousand rubles for the document.
This is more than twice the cost of the official test: it costs a migrant worker three thousand rubles.
The fact that the most important immediate task is to protect the system from corruption, so that the certificates can not be bought easily, both officials and civil rights activists agree.
For the moment, the authorities can only promise guest workers who fall through the test for the first time that they will get time for a basic language course.
In addition, newcomers without language skills are offered jobs in areas where no active understanding with people is necessary.
Interior Ministry ignores illegal arms market
Proportion of legal weapons in criminal offences extremely low
The Russian Interior Ministry plans to tighten the gun law for private gun owners.
The authorities are reacting to the recent events: wounded in shootings at weddings and seven dead in the atrocity of Moscow lawyer Dmitry Winogradov.
Police want to ban the use of non-lethal weapons in public and raise the age for possession of firearms from 18 to 21 years.
The proposal was supported by the Chairman of the Duma Committee on Security and Anti-Corruption, Irina Jarovaja, and promised that the amendments to the Arms Act would be submitted to the Duma shortly.
Not everyone is satisfied with the fact that the Russian authorities want to fight the problems by "attracting the screws".
On the Internet, an open letter was published, whose author - representatives of various arms associations - ask the authorities to distance themselves from "meaningless aggravations".
The percentage of crimes with registered weapons is very low, said the criminal lawyer, Vasily Lesnikov, the Russian service of the BBC.
According to statistics from the Ministry of the Interior, 142 crimes involving the use of registered weapons were committed over the course of six months in 2012, while a total of 1,168 thousand crimes were recorded for the same period.
The authors of the open letter are convinced that a tightening of the law for private gun owners will not deter criminals from using the black market.
At the moment, according to the authors, you can find any weapon in Moscow for little money.
Meanwhile, the Interior Ministry stresses that the spread of illegal weapons is under control.
Suppliers: from the factories to the officers
The weapons reach the black market through several channels.
There are five such main channels, says a former Colonel Viktor Baranez, who worked in the Ministry of Education and the General Staff for ten years.
Screenshot of a website that accepts weapons orders
The first channel is the army or military, i.e. weapons that were stolen during the fighting in the Caucasus.
“The weapons were stolen by both Russian officers and the Caucasians themselves,” Baranez said.
On the second channel there are illegal weapons that are stolen from law enforcement by criminals.
Baranez explains that this includes weapons stolen both from the police’s weapons chambers and directly from law enforcement officials.
Other illegally sold weapons come from military weapons warehouses.
In many military camps, there were frequent explosions.
"There is evidence that in some cases it was arson to cover up the lack of weapons," the former military official said.
According to Baranez, the weapons manufacturers also make a contribution to the black market.
“Today, there are countless private arms factories that cannot withstand international competition and, therefore, are slinging weapons at hand on the black market, such as in Moscow,” the expert reports.
Another channel of the black market is smuggling.
Especially many guns and rifles come from poor countries such as Kyrgyzstan.
“There is a production of its own, sometimes artisanal, as well as a mafia that organizes the smuggling,” the former military official explains.
Where do the weapons come from?
Experts calculated the share of each of the five channels in the supply of illegal weapons to the black market.
In 2011, a report was written by the Center for Problem Analysis and Public Administration.
The experts analyzed reports from the Ministry of the Interior and the Federal Service for State Statistics, criminological literature and publicly available data on portals on the topic of weapons.
The vast majority of illegal weapons, according to investigators, come from the army and law enforcement agencies.
Half of all weapons on the black market are there because of the “guilt of those responsible for dealing with weapons in their work,” the report said.
According to the data of the researchers, 17% of the weapons come from conflict areas, 14% go back to theft in the production of weapons, and 5% come from illegal excavations.
A sales consultant at a gun store who doesn’t want to be named assures that weapons found in illegal excavations have long since been bought by no one, as they are out of date.
According to him, it is more common for traders to obtain the supply in a weapons warehouse.
A gun, such as a TT pistol, is purchased via a ferry.
The weapon is issued and handed over through the fence.
“The dealer brings the gun into the city and sells it there for 900 euros per piece with two magazines,” he says.
"Of course, the police know everything and therefore, if they are unable to comply with the crime detection plan, periodically carry out control purchases from dealers who offer illegal weapons," the sales consultant adds.
"Like in a luxury store"
Buyers and sellers most often find each other through acquaintances.
