In the United States, fast food and supermarket workers strike
One in four U.S. youths at some point sits behind the checkout desk of Mc Donald's
In recent days, there have been massive protests across the U.S. against low wages in Walmart stores and restaurants of popular fast-food chains such as Mc Donald’s, Burger King, Taco Bell, Wendy’s and Kentucky Fried Chicken.
Still, no one can predict whether the protests will continue to swell or whether they will soon be out of the air again.
The protests are supported by trade unions and several left-wing non-profit organizations.
In addition to raising the modest wages of ordinary Walmart and fast food employees, the organizers of the protests are pursuing the goal of founding unions.
So far, this sector of the economy is hardly organized by trade unions.
46 cents a year?
The protests began last week after Thanksgiving, the so-called Black Friday, where U.S. sales were held, attracting millions of customers, sometimes resulting in handcuffs.
On that day, some Walmart employees, of whom there are 2.2 million worldwide, laid down their jobs and, along with unions and left-wing activists, struck down branches of the chain whose target group is low- and middle-income individuals.
Walmart sells everything from diapers to hunting rifles and car batteries to vacuum cleaners, eggs and milk.
The goods in the Walmart branches are on average between 8 and 27% cheaper than in large supermarkets.
That’s why many of the low-paid Walmart employees only buy in at their own workplace.
The prices and product range made Walmart one of the largest companies in the United States.
According to critics, Walmart can often only sell the goods so cheaply because the employees are poorly paid.
The latter also complain about difficult working conditions, for example, missing forklifts or hand scanners.
The participants of the Black Friday protests demanded wage increases and expressed their anger that the contribution to the company's health insurance had increased from 30 to 100 dollars a month.
A typical Walmart employee who earns $9.5 an hour could not afford this increase, they said.
Researchers from the University of California, Berkeley, show that if the company raised the average wage to $12 an hour, it would cost Walmart $3.2 billion.
That’s about 1.1% more than they’re donating now for wages.
If Walmart were to completely shift the pay increases to customers, every purchase would cost them only 46 cents more in the future.
For them, that would be an increase of just $12.39 per year compared to today.
Advocates of Walmart are satisfied that there were only protests in nine states, and these did not cause any losses to the company.
Black Friday lasted in its store from 8 p.m. on Thursday to midnight the next day, and during that time, Walmart sold about 5,000 items per second.
In total, Walmart cashiers executed nearly 100 million transactions on Black Friday.
The company’s spokesman, Dan Fogelman, claimed in an interview on the left-wing Huffington Post website that a total of “less than five” Walmart employees were laid off and the protest was merely “another PR trick” by the union that organized the protests.
"Free cash!"
The protests continued this week in New York City, where their target was not Walmart branches (which are not wanted in this progressive city and therefore do not exist so far), but McDonald's and other low-cost restaurants.
McDonald's says the company sells billions of servings, and yet you're not granted sick days, and you're not paid for your honest work!
Jumaane Williams, Member of the New York City Council
Currently, the minimum wage under federal and New York law is $7.25 an hour.
In fast food restaurants, the minimum wage is gradually raised, but not too much, and on average, their ordinary employees in New York get $8.90 an hour.
No one in this expensive city deserves less.
How it is possible to get out of New York with so little money is incomprehensible to me.
There was a time when almost a quarter of all U.S. youths were behind the counter at McDonald's after school, but the youths were still living with their parents.
Hardly anyone saw the main source of income or planned to stay there longer.
Now, in interviews with McDonald’s employees, I constantly meet people who complain that they have to make up for this salary and sometimes even feed their children.
On the other hand, there is a comment in the forum of the Wall Street Journal, the author of which notes that it is irresponsible to have children if you do not know how to feed them.
Participants in the protests, which began Thursday morning at 6:30 a.m. in front of McDonald’s on 40th Street and Madison Avenue, demanded that cashiers and chefs of fast-food restaurants receive a minimum wage of $15 an hour, more than doubling the current minimum wage.
They continued to call for the formation of trade unions in the fast food industry.
U.S. law prohibits corporate management from standing in the way of this goal and from reprimanding or dismissing union members.
On the other hand, corporate management does not make it easy for them.
However, the establishment of trade unions in the fast food sector is also difficult for objective reasons.
The main reason is the high staff turnover.
Unsatisfied
There were loud protests that day also in front of many other fast food restaurants in Manhattan.
The climax of the protests was a gathering at lunchtime in front of McDonald's in Times Square, where some local Democrats spoke, including city council member Jumaane Williams, who said, "McDonald's says it sells billions of servings, and yet you are not granted sick days, and you will not be paid for your honest work!"
The protesters were also supported by other prominent New York Democrats, for example, Mayoral candidate Bill De Blasio, who said that "we should jointly support the fast-food workers so that they can get a fair wage and achieve the economic prosperity that every New Yorker deserves!"
According to the New York Times, this was the largest action of its kind in the history of the U.S. fast food industry.
However, only a few hundred people were on site, not all of whom are employed in the fast food industry, where tens of thousands work in New York.
It is not yet clear whether the spark of these protests will mobilize entire masses.
"The brain can only be moderately outsmarted so far"
The topic of augmented reality, popular among followers of modern technologies, has recently been usually perceived by the lens of a special glasses.
First, Google presented a working model at its annual conference in the summer, then in November it was announced that Microsoft had also filed a corresponding patent.
However, in a conversation with the head of the Interactive 3D Technologies Group at Microsoft’s lab in Cambridge Shahram Izadi, it becomes clear that the glasses were only a transit station for the company’s scientists.
It stimulates the ability to manipulate virtual objects in the air with bare hands and create virtual free spaces.
- Please briefly describe which research your group is doing.
- We deal with the interaction of man and machine, but want to expand the limits of this interaction.
So far, most of humanity has been stuck in the phase of working with pixels on flat screens, which are sometimes also touched.
However, we want to predict 5-10 years and predict the radical changes of this interaction.
For example, the Xbox console and Kinect sensors are a step forward, and nowadays no Xbox is sold without Kinect, as everyone is interested in motion control.
- What else awaits us in the future?
- Although Kinect has brought the interaction to a physical level, a lot is still happening on the flat screen, sometimes in 3D.
The input of information (the system receives more data) could be improved, the output has not yet been decisive.
We are trying to change that, working on real three-dimensional imaging systems based on different technologies, including projections.
We need to release the computer world into our physical world and make it more tangible.
However, it is necessary that not only the user, but also his environment is recognized.
Then we could complement the real world much easier with virtual objects.
And first of all, we should get rid of these shady virtual reality helmets!
- What do you think about voice control?
It’s popular, but isn’t it overrated?
- It is certainly not the all-purpose solution, as it raises questions about privacy, because you do not always want to inform all those around you about his actions and intentions.
Actually, any kind of interaction with computers is good, but each in its particular niche.
For example, in the area of controlling objects in public places, we worked on a project in which we experimented with short and short, rather than with exaggerating gestures.
The gestures were not recorded by the object camera, but by a bracelet that recorded the movements of the bones and muscles.
It is still relatively large, but could theoretically be reduced to the size of a wristwatch.
But overall, the future belongs to mixed control types, such as gesture and language.
- How's that?
- For example, would you ask me to supply you with this sprinkler?
They say it and point it out at the same time.
- I usually just say it.
- Oh, that would be very hard to tell.
- Does this mean that you want the user to adapt to what a machine can afford at the time and what not?
- Not necessarily, but this is about a mutual approach.
I think that in the near future we will have to work primarily on the development of new types of sensors that allow us to more accurately capture people’s reactions.
These can be laser sensors, for example, because they offer a good resolution at depth, which is very important.
- What demands do you make on modern cameras based on your work with the Xbox Kinect sensors?
Is it lack of resolution, depth or something else?
- The current generation is basically a good starting point for our work in the field of three-dimensional recognition.
Of course, 8 megapixels with a speed of 1000 fps would not be bad.
But the main thing is not the megapixels themselves, but the quality of the matrix and the depth.
In this way, all current technologies are not good enough for us, as the developers of the algorithms have more work.
Not only the resolution along the X and Y axes, but also along the Z axis must be taken into account.
The speed and number of images per second are also important.
The movements of man are extremely dynamic and frankly, the current 30 fps, especially for gestures, are not enough.
In our laboratory in Redmond, Stephen Betishes developed a touch sensor with an adjustable processing delay between 1 to 100 milliseconds, with today’s commercial sensors being closer to the second value (60 to 100).
Not everyone understands how much this affects the interaction of man and machine.
For my work I needed just such a device, only without touch control and with more images per second.
- Shouldn't the number of cameras be increased?
- Kinect currently works with three "cameras", one of which is actually an infrared transmitter and the other a receiver for the reflected signal.
And the third camera is actually an ordinary RGB camera.
It is not used to calculate the depth of the object.
More cameras might solve the problem...
Or increase the problem, as more calculations would be necessary.
It would be nice to have a flexible, Kinect-like system where we could play with different camera attachments to see how that helps us in the three-dimensional determination of a position.
If I remember correctly, unlike Google, Microsoft did not present its glasses to the public.
Don’t you think that in terms of the application of augmented reality technology in everyday life, glasses have the best prospects?
- Of course, it is not pleasant to always keep a smartphone in the raised hand on the road, but I think the following: The best option would be a "changing" augmented reality, in which we could switch from the glasses to the smartphone via a cloud,
The glasses are a personal gadget and in this lies their strength (privates can only be seen), but at the same time their weakness, because an extended reality by means of glasses prevents you from working together with others on virtual objects.
Imagine for a moment that the manipulation of virtual holograms in the air is accessible not only to Tony Stark from Iron Man, but also to normal mortals.
There is a problem that critics often point to: there is no tangible reaction!
The hands don’t feel anything at all.
What answers does your group want to give to this objection?
- In my lectures I often speak of the fact that the augmented reality represents the seventh breakthrough in the interaction between man and machine.
I think the eighth breakthrough could well be the integration of tactile perception.
An interesting method is currently the use of the second hand as a somewhat unusual projection medium.
She feels the pressure very well!
But there are also technologies that are actually aimed at giving the "pictures in the air" something hand-holding, for example, the interference of some directed ultrasound beams at a certain point where the finger is located, a feeling that is currently still as weak as someone breathing over the handballs.
There are also ligaments for the wrist that affect the nerve endings in the fingers, also this is a potential direction.
- Have you tried to outsmart the brain?
It makes you think that it senses what it should feel when it is just seeing something?
- That's a good idea, so we haven't tried it yet.
Here is another task that we will have to contend with for a long time, namely to make a person who is physically in a closed space believe that he is instead in an open, practically infinite space; here we are working on concepts with treadmills (other than in gyms), moving platforms as well as large balls.
So far, the brain can only be moderately outsmarted, and we still have many years of hard work ahead of us.
This is precisely what makes the work in the field of virtual reality so attractive for a researcher: We are only at the beginning of many topics.
