Birth in Space
Earth is in danger.
Global warming or collision with a killer asteroid.
Caravans of spaceships with Earthlings on board are searching for a replacement planet.
In order to save humanity, the important question arises, how can we reproduce in weightlessness or on the replacement planet?
In my opinion, there are not many options.
In fact, there are only two real planets that we could at least hypothetically inhabit.
"It's Mars and Venus," says astronomer Vladimir Surdin of the Sternberg Astronomical Institute.
However, while the conditions on Mars are comparatively life-friendly, there is a temperature of 500 degrees on the surface of Venus.
Life would only be possible at high altitude or in the orbit of Venus, i.e. in space.
The researchers first discussed the question of reproduction in space with regard to the flora.
Already half a century ago, experiments with plants were carried out.
The fourth generation of the peas grown in orbit did not differ in the slightest from the terrestrial species.
It was followed by the breeding of insects, more precisely of tiny fruit flies (Drosophila), in orbit.
In 1979, quail eggs were sent into space to explore how weightlessness affects the development of embryos.
A normal chick develops.
But then the problem begins.
“The problem is that the chick has to stop; it has to be able to stand on its feet and start moving,” explains Vladimir Sychew, head of the laboratory at the Institute for Medical Biological Problems RAN.
Without solid ground, the chicks squandered themselves wildly.
Ten hours later, the instincts of the newborns completely dulled.
The chicks did not respond to light and noise.
Four days later, they just died.
"Two times we let chicks hatch and then we stopped the whole thing, because it is simply impossible to work with them there," Vladimir Sychew says of the failed experiment with chicks in space.
The last breeding cage with animals flew into orbit 16 years ago.
In the spring of 2013 the experiments will continue.
However, on the biosatellite "Bion" there will be only same-sex species.
There was an experiment with rats that were already sent into space fertilized.
In principle, nothing special was found.
"This was just with the biosatellites, but again it was just a single experiment, and the research needs to be continued," Sychev said.
After landing, the space rats were given offspring.
The problem of reproduction directly in space could not be solved so far.
The task is difficult.
Animals that are torn from their natural habitat simply cannot follow their reproductive drive.
Unlike animals, humans can do this in principle.
Homo sapiens is capable of abstract thinking and can create a similar emotional background.
From ethical considerations, such experiments are not carried out.
Women have been flying into space for 50 years.
The biggest risk was at Tereshkova.
The most valuable thing that humanity possesses is the female organism.
Our gulls flew away, and no one on Earth could have answered the following question: Does it survive spaceflight?
Will she be able to give birth to a child after this flight?
"Finally, no one answered this question," says space veteran Wachtang Watschnadse.
In June 1964, just one year after her space flight, the first female cosmonaut, Valentina Tereschkova, gave birth to a daughter.
The child's father, Andriyan Nikolayev, was also a cosmonaut.
In 1988, the second woman in space, Swetlana Sawizkaja, who was in orbit twice and even performed work outside the spacecraft, gave birth to a son.
However, there is still a risk.
We only have a very few cosmonauts, where after long flights everything went well and they got healthy offspring.
"The more, the more dangerous it is even when flying into orbit," concludes cosmonaut Valeri Polyakov, hero of the Soviet Union and hero of the Russian Federation.
And yet humanity must look for new ways in biotechnology, radiation protection and the generation of artificial gravity.
The hydro laboratory in the Cosmonaut Preparation Center is a mandatory station during flight preparation.
Here in a floating state, the cosmonauts gain routine for work in open space.
The water represents weightlessness.
Although adults find water to be pleasant, it is a foreign environment; however, infants perceive water as a natural element.
It is as if the little Ichtyanders bear witness that life in the land rose from the ocean.
There is a connection between the fact that a child is in the mother’s womb for about 9 months in the amniotic fluid, and the fact that it can then get used to water more easily.
In principle, this is logical, since from birth to the first swim just 2 weeks pass.
“This is not enough time to forget something,” says baby swimming instructor Marina Aksenova.
While for a newborn baby, weightlessness is a much more natural condition, the woman does not come out without gravity.
In the state of weightlessness, the abdominal and pelvic muscles form very quickly and thus also decreases the ability to squeeze the child out.
All right, let's get around the birthing aids.
For example, the birth could also take place in a special chamber to squeeze the child out.
"But what happens then?" is the not insignificant question of Valeri Poljakov.
On the other hand, the child also needs artificial gravity.
Without feeling the Earth's pull, the organism cannot form the skeleton and the muscles.
A newborn child cannot be put into a load suit in orbit like an adult for training.
He will simply miss what is of elementary importance to his life.
“This experiment, which we are doing together, namely the birth of a child in a foreign environment, will lead to the birth of a disabled person, a completely unsuitable person,” says Igor Pestow, head of the Bioethics Commission of the Institute for Medical-Biological Problems RAN.
So far, the birth of children in space is just a theory.
At some point, however, it becomes a reality when the inhabitants of Earth in their spaceships go to a distant planet, which becomes the home for their descendants born in space.
