As far as the authorities are concerned, the German counterpart to the NK<0xC3><0x9A> is the Bundesrechnungshof, which is structured in a similar way to ours and also has a college, which is formed only slightly differently.
Competences are also comparable to a certain extent, but Germany is a state, i.e. there are also these courts in the individual federal states - in this the German system differs from ours.
The BRH can only control federal funds, which corresponds to our state funds.
Public funds, which are managed by the districts and municipalities in our country, are subject to the control of the state accounting offices.
As far as German legislation is concerned, is it simpler than ours?
In general, I would not like to compare this without concrete information; nevertheless, in some respects Germany is often referred to as a model, although it certainly cannot be said that Germany is better at everything.
Is it because the testers are better?
That is not certain, but as I said: I do not like such comparisons very much.
It should also be noted that those countries that are a model for us are also struggling with problems.
Otherwise, they wouldn't have anything to do with cooperating with our authority, would they?
As for the Czech legislation, what was the significance for your authority of the renewal of the procurement law, do you already feel any impact?
In view of the fact that this novella is only in force for a short time, it does not have an effect on our examinations so far.
Since our checks take place at a later date, there is a certain delay to be expected.
So far, we are more likely to have an impact in the preparatory phase of future controls - so we have introduced the new control instrument "Recognition of risks of uneconomicity" and with this almost 14,000 public contracts reviewed and analyzed - here the changes will of course have an impact, as the thresholds have changed, the conditions for certain types of changes have changed.
Do you see the passing of this law as more positive, or will the system be burdened with further red tape?
I think this law is definitely a step in the right direction and I hope this assumption is confirmed.
However, the problem may arise that the rules become "stricter" and can no longer be adhered to.
Already under the previous rules, persons subject to an audit are accountable to the bearer (for example, in the case of an operational programme of regional policy, the Regional Council) in such a way that any non-compliance with the procurement law is tantamount to a violation of budgetary discipline.
Does it make sense to tighten the law?
I don't think so.
The system must exclude those who want to attack and abuse the system, and not punish those who have committed a formal error that does not affect the actual decision-making.
Such a system only puts even greater pressure on the bureaucracy.
Where's the way out?
First of all, let us say which path is not objective.
The Prime Minister recently said that the ODS would not illuminate the entrepreneurs with controls of the so-called "black system" - what exactly does that mean?
Is the black system now banned or allowed?
A law must have its validity, and if something is prohibited by law, then the head of government cannot simply come, and the control office, whose duty is now to control compliance with the law, interfere with its work.
He can say, "We change the law and allow the thing," but he can't say that we do it as if nothing were.
The procurement law contains relatively strict rules on the formal execution of certain transactions - and this is also true for the protection of public competition.
On the other hand, it is also tragic if the bidder with the best offer is excluded solely due to defects in form.
The law will never be perfect, but it must be applied correctly - and that is what I think is missing.
