Next year we would also like to perform at the Czech House in New York, and I personally - if we are already in the United States - would like to associate this with performances in Washington and Chicago.
Your plans abroad are not exactly small, so far you have already performed in Madrid, Brussels, London or Moscow.
The Tap Tap is a group of people with disabilities.
How do you manage these trips logistically and organizationally?
It’s not as bad as it seems at first glance.
Five of our members are wheelchair users, i.e. the wheelchairs have to be transported in the luggage compartment. In addition, of course, we have to carry a lot of instrument cases and other luggage...
Nevertheless, so far it has always worked without problems, <0xC4><0x8C>SA and British Airways have always been very well prepared for us, that I have sometimes wondered already.
Even in Moscow, where we were recently, there were no problems.
Through your travels abroad, you will have a comparison of what it looks like in the individual countries with accessibility, how to deal with disabled people there, etc.
How have you experienced these things so far?
After Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other cities where everything works better than in our country, we witnessed in Russia that everything in the East is still in its beginnings.
Compared to Prague, Moscow is absolutely not suitable for the disabled, where it is still unusual for someone in a wheelchair to travel alone in the city center.
It is not even self-evident that you leave a wheelchair user in the elevator, for example.
Fortunately, there are also associations that try to point out the problems of people with disabilities.
And in what way do we have to catch up with the more developed countries?
There are a lot of things we hang out in...
However, it should also be noted that an improvement in the situation always depends on the efforts of those affected.
In London and Madrid, it is absolutely common for people with severe disabilities to move independently in public spaces, go to museums, use toilets, etc.
But it is not very common for a larger group of disabled people to actively participate in social events, in which we are a little ahead of the West with the band The Tap Tap!
Respect for the public and accessibility is one thing, but only when significant athletes, artists, actors, politicians or lawyers come from our ranks will things really begin to change.
So far, these are only individual cases of particularly strong-willed personalities.
The Tap Tap is currently very popular, but if we go back a few years, what motivated you to start a band in 1998?
At that time, I started as a tutor at the Jedli<0xC4><0x8D>ka Institute, where I met many young people who were interested in working with something intensive.
And since I am a musician myself and play saxophone, among other things, I founded a music company together with a colleague.
Well, and over time, as our presenter, L<0xC3><0xA1><0xC4><0x8F>a Angelovi<0xC4><0x8D>, used to say, something gets out of control (laughs).
The band has only been known in recent years, or am I wrong?
It is true that the collaboration with well-known singers has helped us; in addition, we have also started to actively promote ourselves.
We have become aware that if you do something and it is not visible to the outside, your own performance does not exist in a certain sense.
Thanks to the EU funding, we can also afford good lecturers, high-quality equipment and so on.
Was it your goal to make it this far with The Tap Tap?
From the beginning, I felt the potential that things could be handled differently.
In show business today, one often copies the other.
This is logical in its own way, since everything new is carefully considered and only accepted after a long time.
There are only a few truly unique things, and I dare to say that tap tap is one of them.
The first impression that the viewer usually has is, of course, pity; this is only natural...
But this compassion is absolutely superfluous, because people with disabilities are not lonely and abandoned beings that we should regret.
It is people who can live a full life and develop, if they have the necessary means to do so.
I always say that when people with disabilities succeed in something, it is not only a progress for themselves, but for the whole society.
Was it also helpful for this success that you are a strict boss, as you hear from many people?
If you want to do something good, you must not compromise on many things and must also demand a certain discipline.
This is, in my opinion, completely normal.
Some come to us with romantic performances, and if they then find that they have rehearsals twice a week, have to complete preparatory phases and spend a lot of time on concert tours, then the enthusiasm of many quickly fades.
But this is how it works everywhere, in every band that wants to work seriously and achieve something.
