Poland and Space.
Last week, at a meeting of the Council of Ministers of the ESA member countries, Poland was admitted as the 20th member of this space agency, making it the second member country from the former Eastern Bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a member of ESA on 12 November 2008).
Poland began a close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and participated in several ESA projects in the following years.
Poland’s journey into space, of course, began much earlier.
Even before the Second World War, Polish space enthusiasts were engaged in space travel, and this did not always lead to understanding.
I recall, for example, the lecture by A. <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld on 6 December 1933 at the Warsaw Observatory, in which the author presented thoughts from his pioneering work "Entrance to the Cosmonautics".
However, the ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the audience cold, and years later <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld still remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski had shown interest in his work.
<0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld won the Prix REP-Hirsch, founded by Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch, in 1934 for "Entrance to the Cosmonautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899-1966) later became an important advocate of astronomy and space travel.
In Polish journals he published hundreds of articles and wrote several books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski’s globally recognized contribution to the development of space travel was recognized, among other things, by naming one of the craters on the far side of the moon after him.
Already in 1925, a railway train was built in Poland, for which a rocket propulsion was planned.
Unfortunately, the author of the draft and the details of this project remained unknown.
It is not even clear whether the missile should be used to launch or to brake the draisines.
The information on this comes exclusively from the contemporary press.
In 1933, the Polish infantry began to deal with rocket-propelled guns.
The research was conducted by the Kom<0xC3><0xB3>rka Techniki Uzbrojenia Institute in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Prof. Gustav Mokrzyckiegi.
From the documents handed down, it is clear that the research had advanced to the stage of practical tests.
The research was then interrupted by the invasion of the German Wehrmacht.
In 1937, Rohozinski's design of a photoelectric hunting missile appeared in the press, and the following year the work "Rakieta - torpedoa powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by the author Leliwa-Krzywoblocky appeared.
Both projects dealt with the military use of rocket propulsion.
Shortly before the war, all projects for the military use of missile technology were coordinated by the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy).
The committee was established in 1937, but after two years of work, its work was completed from the beginning of the war.
Other articles on spaceflight were published after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Space Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautzyczne) in the Polish press.
The first mention of this society takes place in 1954 in the November issue of the magazine Problemy, in which four extensive articles on space travel are devoted.
The article by Prof. M. Subotowicz contains the proposal to establish a space company.
At the time, there were already the first projects on satellite technology, and it was to be expected that the exploration of space would have a future.
Already in its beginnings in 1956, the Polish Space Agency (PTA) sought to join the International Space Federation (ISS), founded in 1951, and in fact the PTA became a full member in the autumn of 1956.
The following year, the first PTA Chairman, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902–1959), became the Deputy Chairman of the International Space Federation.
He held this position until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the PTA has been instrumental in the development of the extremely successful meteorological rocket (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), the first Polish rocket for scientific research.
The first type, the RM-1, was completed in 1957, the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
The rocket with a maximum flight height of 1800 m was about 80 cm long and did not quite weigh 5 kg.
Later, an improved version, the RM-1A, was built, and in 1959, in the B<0xC5><0x82><0xC4><0x99>d<0xC3><0xB3>w Desert, flight tests began with the two-stage rocket RM-2.
The rocket was 1.4 m long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another stage of development should already be able to do real scientific work - the rocket RM-34 should reach a flight height of up to 14.5 km and be used for the observation of high-altitude winds.
In 1962, however, further development was halted.
The successor to the first RM rockets was the Meteor-1 rocket, which was developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage rocket, its total length was 510 cm and the starting weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types (Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed from this rocket, which differed in the size of the transport space for scientific instruments.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a carrying capacity of 0.4 liters, Meteor-1B over 0.34 liters and Meteor-1C over 0.62 liters.
The maximum flight height for all three types was 37 km.
From 1965 to 1968, the Aeronautical Institute developed the Meteor-2 rocket, the first flight tests of which began in October 1970.
Meteor-2 had a starting weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a payload of 10 kg to a height of about 60 km.
After that, the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
Poland also joined the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960, which was followed two years later by the establishment of a national COSPAR committee.
As part of the Intercosmos program, Poland also participated in space exploration with Soviet satellites, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after the Czech Vladim<0xC3><0xAD>r Remek.
Repeal of the law on non-profit work is not a solution.
Last week, the Constitutional Court overturned the law on non-profit work.
This decision gave rise to a lively discussion in the public.
It is certainly interesting to look at the problem from a broader perspective.
The liberal economic systems in the EU and in the globalised world are based on the principle of unregulated economic competition.
In the end, this means that the individual economies are in permanent conflict with each other.
The reason for this is the principle of free trade and the free, unrestricted movement of private capital, which goes hand in hand with unrestrained financial speculation.
Due to the large differences in the value of labor (wage), price tensions arise.
This term is to be understood as referring to a condition in which the manufacturer attempts to compete by importing favourable goods in economic competition by "undercutting" the competition in order to gain a larger market share and increase its profit.
On a large scale, this means for most companies to move their manufacturing abroad or to buy cheaply there, or to give up their business. The result is a high unemployment in countries with comparable high labor costs.
Since private capital bears no social responsibility and therefore no responsibility for the unemployment caused by it, government spending necessarily increases.
This situation is further exacerbated by the fact that the entrepreneurs are absolutely unwilling to pay their taxes and thereby compensate for the overall economic and social damage caused by them.
This situation is generally known, so that specific statistics are superfluous at this point.
The ruthless practice of private capital creates in individual economies a situation in which governments are forced to compete with each other in order to artificially lower the social level of their own population and thus attract foreign capital into the country.
In other words, governments deliver their own population without regard for the social consequences to private capital.
This is reflected in particular in amendments to applicable laws.
The aim of these measures is to force its own people to accept the dictates of private capital, especially in the wage sector.
This is done, on the one hand, by economic coercion in the event of long-term unemployment, and on the other, by the curtailment of workers' rights.
The result is growing poverty, as well as ever-increasing differences between rich and poor.
In Germany, for some years now, there have been public food outlets for the poor who are no longer able to feed themselves through their own work.
The number of people affected is already in the millions.
In the course of increasing the competitiveness of the German economy, there are regular cases in which workers receive such a low wage that the state must increase their income to the subsistence minimum.
Such a scandal was also uncovered in the case of auxiliary forces employed in the German Bundestag.
The austerity measures of virtually all EU southern states will undoubtedly lead to the same state in which people are forced to emigrate under the pressure of a catastrophic collapse of their social level (as was the case in the 19th century), or to work for a hunger wage on the fringes of society, hoping that at some point private investment will be made.
This naturally raises the question of where this capital comes from.
When it comes from another EU country, only poverty migrates from one country to another; or capital stays out of it altogether, because in China, India, Brazil, Turkey, Morocco or Egypt, or in Africa at all, the workers work for a fraction of the European wages.
This applies to all of Latin America.
Liberal theories and the media claim, until further notice, that the state is not allowed to participate with capital in its own economy, and that the planned economy leads to economic disaster.
Private capital insists narrowly on its position that the state is not allowed to intervene in the economy.
But then one has to wonder whether private capital does not influence politics and thus the whole state in its own selfish sense or even direct it.
Here is the clear answer: Yes.
The proof of this is the existence of a practically omnipotent and omnipresent lobby in all states.
The result is a desperate situation in the field of corruption, mutual advantage, a legislation in which practically everything is criminal, but nothing is criminal.
In Germany, the situation is such that, in the absence of finance, a State Ministry entrusts private law firms closely linked to industry with the drafting of bills.
These bills are then passed in the Bundestag.
All violence then no longer emanates from the people, as the Western constitutions proclaim, but from strong financial groups that prefer their own interests.
Evidently, liberal democracies are now rapidly falling into a situation as Appian describes in his work on the crisis of the Roman Republic in the days of Caesar and Pompey: "The state had long since been understood to be in disarray, and the offices were occupied by force.
Against lubricating money, through unlawful easing of benefits or with stone and sword.
The corruption grew unchecked, and the people went to the polls with already bought votes" ... "People with character did not apply for office, so that the state as a result of this decline had no consul for eight months" ... "But they were already really beginning to talk about the fact that the only medicine in this difficult situation was a man's self-rule, and that a strong one would be elected"
As it turns out, today’s society, as in ancient times, is based on the ruthless preference of one’s own advantage, without paying attention to the interests of society as a whole.
Private capital, by its very nature, is not able to recognize and enforce the advantage for the whole of society.
The result, today as then, is an unprecedented decadence of the elites who are not at all striving for deeper reforms.
We must therefore look for the cause of the rise of fascism and communism in the ruthless liberalization of economic systems in the 19th and 20th centuries.
From today's point of view, the downfall of these regimes in favour of liberal democracies can be seen as a certain pause in which the next round is already drawing to a close.
Particularly catastrophic is the fact that today’s elites are facing the possible loss of hundreds of thousands of lives in the future, the humanitarian and social catastrophes of which we are already witnesses today, and the crimes against humanity as we know them from past and recent history, in complete ignorance.
The repeal of the law on non-profit work is not a solution here, at least not a permanent one.
Under pressure from global and European economic competition, the Czech Republic will be forced to continue to look for ways to push the social level of the population down.
This trend is therefore systemic.
The only solution is targeted political and social reforms that increase the state’s participation in the economy, increase the influence of citizens on the government, and weaken the monopoly of private capital in society in favor of the state.
