The movie Argo: When it's worst, call Hollywood
In November 1979, a mob of protesting Islamist students occupied the U.S. Embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats hostage.
For their release, they demanded the extradition of the overthrown Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who had fled to the United States after the revolution, which had guarded the patronage of his regime for decades.
For the American government there was no positive way out of this situation - it could not afford to throw the Shah overboard, as this would have massively damaged the confidence of its allies in other countries.
At the same time, it was unable to enforce the release of the hostages in Iran, where the revolution led to the establishment of a theocratic regime.
It was a severe blow to the reputation of the United States, and the subsequent failure of the violent attempt to free the hostages only made everything worse.
The captured diplomats were finally released after 444 days, after negotiations had been brokered by the Algerian government.
The fate of the hostages brought home a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiments.
The debacle in Iran contributed significantly to Jimmy Carter's defeat of Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film Argo by director and actor Ben Affleck describes an episode of this story that gave the United States a small partial victory.
Immediately before the occupation of the embassy, six embassy employees managed to escape.
This ended after numerous complications in the residence of the Canadian ambassador.
The CIA, in collaboration with the Canadian authorities, managed to bring the refugees out of Iran; in doing so, they were helped by an extravagant story to conceal their true identity – they traveled with Canadian passports disguised as members of a film staff who allegedly visited the country’s filming location for a science fiction film.
Combination of genres
The plan developed by "Exfiltration" expert Tony Mendez also required Hollywood's cooperation.
To make the cover credible, articles about this film project appeared in professional magazines, press conferences were held, and the fictional production company had a real office.
The details of this operation were kept secret for a long time, based on the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck’s film is a special combination of several film genres.
On the one hand, he is a realistic political thriller, but at the same time also a so-called "Caper Movie", i.e. the story of a successful hussar piece such as the film Ocean's Eleven.
As a result, the mood levels change in the film - on the one hand, the documentary scenes from Tehran (in the title sequence, iconic contemporary photographs are shown, and even in the film version of the same situations there are no big differences).
On the other hand, the loose passages from Hollywood, which ironically and slightly exaggerated, therefore come.
And then there are the scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions - men in suits at the meeting table, on the official floors, on the phone...
Ben Affleck has made a remarkable start to his career with this film.
From a smiling actor has become a respectable director, and even as an actor he is no longer the target of ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film after the crime drama No Child’s Play (Gone Baby Gone, 2007) and the thriller City of No Mercy (2010).
At the same time, it’s Affleck’s first film, not in the director’s native Boston.
The sense of the atmosphere of the place was one of the features that lifted the previous films of this director from the standard of Hollywood.
However, Affleck also proves this feeling in Argo, where Tehran is “played” by Canada.
The best scenes of the film play in the streets and show the reconstruction of events that really took place - the entrance sequence of the storming of the message is very impressive in its clarity, yet conveys the feeling of confusion and unpredictability that occurs when history moves somewhere.
Affleck and his team achieve a similar effect even in fictional scenes (the wrong film staff on a bazaar in Tehran).
Too much action in too many places
The director also had to deal with the fact that the story does not actually offer many exciting scenes in the cinematic sense.
But with the few, he works quite successfully, sometimes he helps the reality a little - which then does not always seem so elegant (the scenes in which the impending crisis at the airport in Tehran is averted by a phone call in America, or even the chase on the runway, seem somewhat artificial).
The weakness of Argo is its too wide dispersion, which is due to the need to show too much action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman are very charming in their roles as Hollywood employees, but their characters deserve more space, and thus they are far from alone in the film.
Affleck’s film loses some of its traction and is a film that can be followed with some interest and at the same time the design and the retro style reminiscent of a thriller from the 70’s can be tasted.
However, it only arouses enthusiasm.
However, as a reminder of a piece of history that is still alive in some way today, and as proof of how far-fetched the notions of the almighty and all-knowing secret services are, it is sufficient.
