The MVRDV architects prove that the true adventures are not only in the mind - with the example of Spijkenisse and the recently built B<0xC3><0xBC>cherberg - 2 photos
“I find the building funny, it looks futuristic, and finally there’s something interesting to see again,” says Lisette Verhaig, a passerby on the side of the road.
And Stefan Spermon, IT technician in a nearby large company, says: "Yes, it's nice, the house."
But I wonder why we still need a library today.
They all have internet, iPad and e-books.
No one goes to one of these old-style libraries today voluntarily, right?
Spijkenisse, a sleepy town that hardly needs to be visited at the gates of Rotterdam, is a remarkable record holder.
The 80,000-strong community has the lowest education rate in the whole of the Netherlands.
In order to counteract this stupid circumstance, a few years ago it was decided to contribute to general education and to reconstruct the seven fictitious bridges depicted on the euro banknotes as beautifully brushed concrete miniatures.
The success of the education offensive was limited.
And so the city fathers realized that there was only one way to become the master of statistics: a library had to come from there!
Winy Maas from Rotterdam’s architectural firm MVRDV, master of bold bar charts and producer of witty, often cynical constructions, took the matter with familiar serenity and appeared at the competition hearing anno 2003 with five books under his arm and a grin on his face.
And while the jury was still squinting and shivering, the cheeky Maas piled his exquisite contribution of size into a pyramid and ended his action-packed speech with the words: "Love the city community!"
So this is it, my proposal for the B<0xC3><0xBC>cherberg of Spijkenisse, for the so-called Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>30 million mountain is being spilt up.
It is part of a revitalization project, which also includes underground garage, supermarket, post office and a few adjacent residential and terraced houses with a total of 50 apartments.
At the beginning of November, the B<0xC3><0xBC>cherberg was awarded the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
The project has also been nominated for the 2012 Dutch National Wood Award.
Thus, the faceless small-town retort, which until now had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian zone and an unfathomably ugly town hall, behind whose white facades one would have tended to suspect a dairy factory to enrich a piece of contemporary architecture.
But above all, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in the history of its existence.
The Long Way to the Book
The first impression: B<0xC3><0xBC>chereldorado under cheese bells.
Although there is a lift that leads through the middle of the mountain massif, the true space and reading delights open with the walking climb of the topography.
The all-glass interior is bright and clear, the burnt clinker floor and the elegant street lights speak the language of a public square.
The urban environment is perfect.
You are already looking for park bench, dog and football playing boys and girls.
And everywhere books, books, books.
“Usually the bookshelves are along the facade, and in the middle is a large, dark room, which is usually uncomfortable and impersonal,” says Winy Maas.
We have turned the classic room configuration upside down and sculpted the reading area from the inside out.
The interior of the B<0xC3><0xBC>cherberg is skillfully used: in the middle are offices, Internet library, chess club, environmental center and home technology center.
A special pleasure are the black bookshelves, which are sometimes wall paneling, sometimes bracing, sometimes stair railings.
Optics, haptics and smell are foreign.
Even inanimate architects and civil engineers shake their heads about the unknown building material.
"We wanted to work with recycling materials here," explains Joop Trouborst, project manager at the municipality of Spijkenisse, at the request of the standard.
And so, one day, in a Frisian farm, we came across a suitable waste product from agriculture.
For many years, in the Netherlands, a thin plastic fleece has been used in greenhouses and fields as a root substrate.
This is cheap and time efficient.
The thin textile lasts one, two seasons, after that it is ripe for the blocking waste.
For the library, the fleece was pressed - for the first time in these quantities - to four centimetres thick plates.
Under the influence of heat and pressure, the so-called Landbouwplastic (KLP) discolors into a dark, homogeneous, load-bearing material that smells a bit like a new car and a bit like a sports shoe.
After 105 steps you have reached the summit.
At the end of the almost 500-metre-long hike, the Literature Café not only rewards you with a fantastic view of the city, but also with Dutch croquettes and potted ficus trees.
They provide the atmosphere, but above all the right humidity in the literary mountains.
Donations for the New Soul
"You wouldn't believe it, but despite the many glass surfaces, this house is a showcase project in terms of ecology," says Trouborst.
It is heated and cooled with earth heat.
Although the B<0xC3><0xBC>cherberg is under a glass fall, even on sunny days the sun shines only briefly inwards.
The wide wooden awnings, which stand transversely to the glass facade, serve as shading and capture much of the sun’s radiation.
The room climate is very pleasant.
The rest is done by fully automatic rollos.
Stefan Spermon, the initial skeptic from the IT industry, already ventured into the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was already there.
And also the TCM teacher Cynthia Bogarde, who even calls the Boekenberg as Spijkenisse's "long overdue soul".
The reason: To open a few weeks ago, every resident was invited to donate a book from his personal collection.
For the first time, this will fill the optical gaps in the library, which is not yet fully stocked - currently 70,000 pieces.
The concept has gone up.
The shelves are filled to the top.
“Nothing is worse than a half-baked library,” says architect Winy Maas.
"I think, thanks to our invitation, every resident now has a certain relationship with this new house.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
And if it is only for decoration.
Thus, MVRDV has succeeded in that royal discipline, which is called identity foundation in the technical jargon.
Spijkenisse has written literary history.
As young and uneducated as she may be.
This is finally a starting point for identity.
