Mexico's Enrique Pena Nieto faces a difficult start
As Mexico’s future president, Enrique Pena Nieto, prepares to take office, Will Grant from the BBC analyses the challenges ahead and the mixed feelings of his people.
At the moment, the traffic in Mexico City is very bad.
Even on better days, this is an ever-closing city, but on Monday a steel ring was erected that shuts down several major transport routes to the capital and causes chaos on the streets.
However, the aim was not to disturb commuters on the way to work, but to prevent demonstrators from reaching Parliament.
On Saturday, Mexico’s new president, Enrique Pena Nieto, will receive the presidency and take over the leadership of the nation.
He is facing a complex task.
Under the outgoing government of Felipe Calderon, Mexico has been able to prove itself economically, but the country is in the grip of a drug war that has already cost 60,000 lives in the last six years.
“My government is strongly committed to reducing violence,” Pena Nieto told U.S. President Barack Obama at the Oval Office earlier this week.
I will propose a new security strategy with which we can achieve this goal.
Prior to joining the U.S. president, Pena Nieto served as governor of his home state of Mexico.
In this densely populated, expansive part of the country surrounding the capital, opinions about the new head of state are divided.
A direct man
In the remote small town of Valle del Bravo, for example, you like to remember him.
Residents of the resort attribute to it the development of tourism and the construction of infrastructure.
To reach the city, you can drive on one of the highways that Pena Nieto built and which represent a great improvement over the fragile, bumpy roads that once existed here.
Plaques with his name also hang outside a modern sports center and an impressive interactive museum on climate change.
"We expect real and lasting changes from him," said his friend and political ally Gabriel Olvera Hernandez, who works as a congressman for the party Pena Nietos, the PRI.
In particular, with regard to security and the economy, we hope for an interesting and real change that our country needs so urgently.
After 81 years in power, the PRI was replaced by Vicente Fox in 2000.
Congressman Olvera admits that after 12 years outside the presidential palace of Los Pinos, the party has high expectations of Enrique Pena Nieto.
The accusations of the opposition, the new president lacks substance, he rejects.
He is a very direct man, very committed and has big plans for the country.
He is an excellent statesman, but above all he is also someone who can listen.
But on the other side of the state, not many people share this view about their former governor.
In Nezahualcoyotl, also known as Ciudad Neza, the contrast to the cobbled streets of Valle del Bravo could not be greater.
The place is hidden under highway crossings and in many ways represents a suburb of Mexico City itself.
And the problems in the community are of a decisive urban nature.
Earlier this year, the military was deployed to fight the drug gangs operating in the neighborhoods, and violence against women is a particularly acute problem.
In the last two years alone, the bodies of dozens of murdered women have been left on a patch of brachland near a large landfill.
During the time of Governor Pena Nieto, over 1,000 women were murdered in the state of Mexico – a statistic that even surpasses that of the city of Ciudad Juarez, which is notorious for its violence and the murders of innocent women.
Critics of Pena Nieto believe that he at least did not adequately address the problem of female murder during his term in office.
But in the worst case, his government has closed its eyes to the problem.
In a concrete building, typical of the downed neighborhood, Irinea Buendia struggles with tears when she shows me photos of her deceased daughter Mariana Luna.
According to the official version of the events, Mariana committed suicide in 2010.
But her family believes she was murdered by her partner.
“When I arrived at her house, it seemed as if her body had been washed,” recalls Senora Buendia.
There were signs that she was beaten, and the sternum had already been inserted.
While her mother tells her story, a picture of Mariana looks down on us from the wall. It is attached next to a cross that carries a single word: justice.
But this, according to the family, has been denied until now.
The authorities have treated me as if I were a speaker, a troublemaker, a troublemaker.
They want you to simply accept their judgment and keep your mouth shut.
“But that’s not possible if there were so many form errors and omissions,” she says.
When President Pena Nieto receives the presidency on Saturday, he also assumes a great responsibility.
Tens of thousands of Mexican families have been victimized by violent crimes over the past six years, and the new president has promised to take special care of this problem during his tenure.
"I hope that as president he is the way he was as governor," says PRI congressman Olvera in Valle del Bravo.
But this is exactly what the families of the victims in Ciudad Neza fear the most.
Prosecutor's Office Says Bradley Manning Didn't Complain About Abuse
Prosecutors deny Bradley Manning's allegations that he was abused in prison
The hearing deals with Manning’s time in military prison in Quantico, Virginia
The defense seeks a rejection of the charge due to harsh conditions of detention
The freedman of the U.S. Army is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents
The prosecutor's office on Friday tried to determine that Army-retarded Bradley Manning - accused of the largest disclosure of confidential information in U.S. history - missed several occasions to complain in military terms about the alleged abuse he suffered.
During a cross-examination of Mannings during a pre-trial hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Maj. Ashden Fein stated that records of weekly visits made by prison officials during Manning's nine-month detention in Quantico, Virginia, did not contain any complaints about his treatment.
A day before the cross-examination, which was held as a result of a defense application to dismiss the charge - Manning had already been sufficiently punished by the harsh detention period - Manning had stated that he had contemplated suicide in prison.
The U.S. military intelligence analyst, who was arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents during his service in Iraq.
The material was then published by WikiLeaks on the Internet.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed Manning as the source of the information.
In Friday’s hearing, Fein and Manning went through the forms that officials had filled out after their meetings with Manning during his detention at Quantico Military Prison, where he had been serving time from July 2010 to April 2011 under heightened conditions of detention.
The officials asked Manning questions and wrote down his answers.
When Fein asked him about the forms on Friday, Manning admitted that he had rated the treatment by his guards as "excellent" and the treatment by the facility as a whole as "very professional".
The forms, according to Fein, contained no complaints about abuse, although the officials had asked Manning directly for his treatment.
Manning replied that he had expressed his concerns orally and that the officials had discussed them with him and indicated that they would deal with them, but they had not been recorded.
“They wrote ‘No Problems’ (after discussing the concerns), and that didn’t necessarily mean I didn’t say anything at all,” Manning said.
The judge, Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he did not complain about his treatment when he met with a committee in January 2011 to investigate the suicidal thoughts he had mentioned on a form a few months earlier.
Manning responded that his intention during this meeting was to downgrade his observational status to “prevent injury.”
The military said it had assigned him this restrictive status – which is one level under the threat of suicide – to his own and the protection of others.
"I wanted to convince employees that I was doing well, and get rid of the observation status to prevent injuries ... in order to achieve a higher quality of life from my point of view," Manning said.
Manning said Thursday he was arrested and transferred to Kuwait, where he was held for nearly two months before being transferred to Quantico Naval Base in Virginia in July 2010.
He said he had contemplated suicide in Kuwait and had become unconscious once due to the heat.
Not being able to know what was happening to him or to the outside world had been burdensome.
“My world shrunk on Camp Arafjon, on this cage together,” Manning said Thursday.
I thought I was going to die in this cage.
When he was moved to Quantico, Manning spent most of his days in a small cell — at least 21 hours and often more than 23 hours — and without company.
They only allowed him a mattress, a blanket, flip-flops, clothes and his glasses.
Manning said he tried to stay on the move because it was forbidden to sleep or even lie down during the day.
He always had to sleep with light entering his cell from the outside.
When he turned around at night and the guards could not see his face, he was awakened to turn back.
In January 2011, Manning's lawyer formally objected to Manning's treatment.
In April 2011, Manning was transferred to Fort Leavenworth, Kansas.
On Friday, Judge Manning also questioned a charge he had leveled in his testimony on Thursday — that he had slept naked in his cell in Quantico for one night and had to stand naked before guards and other prisoners at a morning count.
Manning had stated that he had never had the opportunity to cover himself with his blanket during this count.
In the interview on Friday, Manning said he had closed the door from an order of his guard that he should drop the blanket he could have covered himself with, but admitted that no one had asked him to.
On Thursday, Manning said he had been forced to sleep naked the night before and had previously tried to show an official that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning told the official that he could have used the waistband of his underpants or flip-flops to hurt himself, but did not.
That night, Manning said, his underpants, flip-flops and glasses had been removed from his cell.
His lawyers hope that the judge will at least take into account his detention experiences and drastically reduce his detention, should he be convicted in his trial before the military court, which is set for the beginning of next year.
The defense has indicated that Manning will plead guilty to lesser offenses, while other charges deemed to be too extreme are to be challenged.
The hearing is scheduled to continue this weekend, and the prosecutor's office is expected to justify the conditions of detention.
The Pentagon remains in its position that Manning has been detained in accordance with the provisions that apply to all prisoners held under the highest security safeguards in Quantico.
The charges against Manning include favoring the enemy, unlawful publication of intelligence information on the Internet, transmission of national defense information, and theft of public property or documents.
If he is found guilty in all charges, he faces a life sentence.
My Mexican-American identity crisis.
