Mexico’s relationship with the United States is complicated and full of resentment.
Most Americans probably never waste a single thought that the United States invaded Mexico in 1848 and forced the leadership of the country under pre-emptive gun control to leave them more than half of their territory.
But for Mexicans who think in centuries and not minutes, memories of this event are not to be overlooked.
So as soon as a U.S. government official makes even the mildest criticism of Mexico, you hear - in the Mexican press and among the country's elites - complaints about how the Americans are oppressing the sovereignty of their neighboring country.
And the children of Montezuma go on the path of war.
And yet Mexico’s biggest challenge really lies in its relationship with the more than 35 million Mexican Americans living in the United States.
Want to talk about feelings?
There's more than enough.
Mexico has winners and losers, people for whom the country offers opportunities, and others for whom it does not.
The only reason so many people of Mexican descent live in cities like Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver or San Antonio is that at one point in our family tree, one person – perhaps a parent or grandparent – was not offered a chance in Mexico and emigrated northward.
And in most cases, this person corresponded to a profile - dark-skinned, uneducated, from a poor village, etc.
We are the descendants of these people, and our loyalty is to them.
Not Mexico.
And while we may now be living the American dream, attending good schools, and getting good jobs, we must never lose sight of the fact that it is the American dream that we are living – not the Mexican one.
Our identity may be blurred at times, but as far as our loyalty is concerned, this is not the case.
