But many Mexican Americans I know feel like they don’t belong to either country.
We love the Mexican band Los Tigres del Norte, but also Bruce Springsteen.
One enjoys the best of both worlds, but is not rooted in any of them.
In Mexico, we are seen as Americans.
And in the United States, we are seen as Mexicans.
As I should learn during my trip, there is something that makes this relationship even more complicated: Some Mexican leaders and parts of the educational citizenship want to resume their connections to the diaspora.
They want to use Mexican Americans as temporary “ambassadors” for Mexico, representing their interests in the United States.
We should tell our American colleagues about how great a visit to this country is and put pressure on the political leadership to intensify their ties with Mexico.
Now.
That's not gonna happen.
Too many hurt feelings.
And in the face of unfair income distribution, rampant corruption and drug violence, many of us are not so sure if this is really a great country.
I'm afraid you'll have to go through this alone, Amigos.
That's fair.
