Hmmm.
Maybe we're more "Mexican" than I thought.
Old battles, new Middle East
The ceasefire between Israel and Hamas could prove to be an unexpected pillar of peace
Can there ever be lasting peace between Arabs and Jews in the Middle East?
The latest bloody events seem to stifle such hope in the bud.
Amid the usual blame, countless buildings were laid in rubble and ashes, more than 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis killed — and for the first time, rockets from Gaza near the Israeli metropolis of Tel Aviv and the holy city of Jerusalem were struck.
But while Israelis and Palestinians seem trapped in their historical conflict, the Middle East is changing around them.
The Arab Spring has created a new, uncertain situation, and whether they want it or not – Palestinians and Israelis have become part of this turmoil.
Perhaps this will only lead to more bloodshed.
But there is reason to believe that the deadly stalemate could finally end.
A war that is neither lost nor won
At first glance, optimism seems anything but appropriate in view of the current situation.
Even if the ceasefire agreed on 21 November continues, this week’s fighting has strengthened the hard-fought on both sides.
The leaders of Hamas, the Islamist movement that has controlled the Gaza Strip since 2007, will claim to have pushed back the Israelis, although its group itself had to record large losses.
Although several Hamas leaders have been killed and the 1.7 million inhabitants of the Gaza Strip are being driven into one of the most desolate and densely populated corners of the planet, Israel has so far failed to destroy Hamas.
In fact, Hamas is gaining ground in the West Bank, which is controlled by the rival, moderate Palestinian group Fatah.
And the Hamas leaders could come to the conclusion that they have time on their side.
Just as Islamists have gained influence in the Arab world, Hamas has been able to draw powerful and rich friends to its side.
Turkey, a reinvigorating regional power once considered Israel’s closest Muslim ally, has taken over the Hamas party – just like Qatar, one of the richest and most dynamic Gulf states.
Gleeful Hamas supporters believe that an Islamist crescent is forming around Israel – from Lebanon in the north, where militant Hezbollah has power, to Syria, where rebels of an increasingly Islamist character could stand before the overthrow of Bashar Assad, to Jordan, where Hamas allies threaten the king.
And in particular, the rise of the Muslim Brotherhood under President Muhammad Morsi in Egypt – by far the most populous and most important Arab country – on Israel’s southern flank has permanently changed the region’s balance.
Hosni Mubarak, the secular despot who ruled Egypt for 30 years until his overthrow in 2011, had little time left for Hamas.
In contrast, the Brotherhood is biased against Hamas and its leaders are more dependent on popular views.
In future diplomatic negotiations, Hamas could prove to be an actor that cannot be pushed out even by Israel and the United States.
The Israeli hardliners, on the other hand, draw the opposite conclusion.
From a military point of view, Hamas is no longer a threat.
The Israeli missile defense system, "Iron Dome", has proven itself and many of the Hamas missiles have been destroyed.
At least for a while, Israel will be able to sleep more peacefully.
From a diplomatic point of view, the United States remains steadfast in its position, and many European countries have blamed Hamas for the latest escalations of violence.
Israel has done well in recent years, especially under Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu, who has largely ignored the peace process.
Although rockets from the Gaza Strip have killed about 30 Israelis since 2004, the country has remained relatively free from suicide bombers – not least thanks to the containment facilities that are being carried out in the West Bank and thus in the main part of any Palestinian state. These protect the Jewish settlements, which have always been declared to be under international law.
Netanyahu’s Likud party has allied itself with an even more militant group ahead of the January 22 elections under Avigdor Lieberman.
Why are these sneaky Palestinians also slandering and leaving them their own state?
If they actually had control of the West Bank, wouldn’t they, like their fellow Gazans, fire rockets?
No, it is better to keep them in check behind the wall and punish them if they dare to lift their heads.
Perhaps the hardliners will be able to prevail, but the Arab spring could give them a dash through the bill.
Even if the Islamists now in power in Egypt and other countries have little left for Israel, they will first focus on the difficulties in their own country.
The defense state of Israel is larger than that of its four Arab neighbors combined.
A war with the local superpower will hardly help the new Arab governments in restoring their economy.
That pragmatic President Morsi is teaming up with Barack Obama to achieve a cease-fire could be a promising sign — and perhaps symbolize the beginning of a new era.
Israelis, too, should think more long-term.
While the rest of the Arab world is taking tacit steps toward democratization, Palestinians continue to be deprived of their right to self-determination – a powder keg that will undoubtedly one day explode in Israeli-occupied areas, just as a bus exploded in Tel Aviv this week.
Suppression is already undermining democracy in the Jewish state, and with the growth of the Arab population, this situation will only worsen.
Bloody missions to repress Hamas in the Gaza Strip will increasingly demand their diplomatic tribute over the years.
Both sides need a push from the outside
The correct answer is the one represented by the more reasonable representatives of both sides, the majority of the rest of the world, and by this newspaper: two states in which Israel secedes for security purposes.
The hope, small for the near future, is that the ceasefire will give outsiders more leverage to enforce this solution.
Egypt, along with Turkey and Qatar, must now stop arms deliveries to the Gaza Strip and is better positioned than ever before to convince Hamas of the idea of a Jewish state based on the 1967 borders, complemented by land swaps and a common Jerusalem.
Foreign Arab nations should also move Hamas and Fatah to an agreement.
This would do more to create a Palestinian state than with the upcoming application for UN observer status.
Obama must also play his part in moving Israel to negotiations.
During his first term in office, he missed the idea of his own peace plan.
