Australian Laws for Uniform Cigarette Packaging Come into Force
Health warnings and diseased body parts on neutral green packs that are the same for all tobacco brands
The world’s first uniform cigarette and tobacco packaging laws have come into force in Australia, replacing brand logos and colours with neutral, olive-green lids, which are also printed with drastic images showing sick body parts and infants and children suffering from cigarette smoke.
Apart from the different health warnings and pictures, the only difference between the packages in the brand names printed in identical small font will be from next Saturday.
Australia has introduced the most stringent tobacco packaging regulations in the world.
The Australian government wants to discourage young people from smoking by removing the glamorous image of tobacco use.
In doing so, the government is looking at studies that have shown that people who haven’t started smoking at age 26 are 99% likely to stop smoking even after that.
"You can already see in young children that they understand the message that tobacco companies are trying to promote with their brand image," said Federal Health Minister Tanya Plibersek, citing studies that have shown, for example, that children associate the crown of a logo with the idea of a princess.
Although Australia has one of the lowest smoking rates in the world and the changes will only slightly affect the profits of multinational corporations, other countries are already considering similar steps.
The tobacco lobby fought hard against the laws.
It was said that with the laws, the black market trade would be favored, which would lead to cheaper and more easily accessible cigarettes.
“The laws will lead to serious, unintended consequences,” says Scott McIntyre of British American Tobacco Australia.
Chinese and Indonesian counterfeiters will offer much larger quantities of these products on the streets of Australia.
Others, on the other hand, say that the laws have boosted their business.
Sandra Ha of Zico Import Pty Ltd, a small family-owned company, notes that demand for cigarette butts and silicone lids to cover the unbearable packaging has increased enormously since the British American Tobacco, Britain's Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco companies filed their lawsuits with the Supreme Court of Australia two months ago.
Zico has sold up to 6,000 units to wholesalers and is waiting for new stocks.
For us, this is a good business.
According to experts, the catch in the popularity of social media lies with exactly the population group to which the plan is aimed.
A number of Australian laws have banned tobacco companies from television advertising, banned them from acting as sports sponsors, and forced most retailers to stop exhibiting cigarettes in stores. Now tobacco advertising has moved to the Internet.
The Australian government has banned internet advertising by local companies and sites, but has no influence on international sites.
“Anyone who markets tobacco and only has a small area left to promote their products doesn’t get around the internet,” says Becky Freeman, a health researcher at the University of Sydney.
On social media such as YouTube, Twitter and Facebook, Freeman has found an increase in testimonials about brands written by “very normal people.”
One has to ask the question: Is this just a private person who likes Marlboro cigarettes so much that they even record a video for it – or does a marketing agency have to do with it?
British American Tobacco Australia says the industry is focusing on marketing rather than dealing with the new laws.
It has even gone so far as to pay Ukraine, Honduras and the Dominican Republic to challenge the new regulations – those countries complain to the World Trade Organization about unfair trade restrictions, even though none of the countries conducts greater trade with Australia.
A WTO decision is expected in mid-2013.
According to Plibersek, the government has held talks with other countries considering similar packaging laws.
In 2001, Canada was the first country to issue photographic warnings.
These have now been extended to more than 40 countries, including Brazil, Turkey and Ukraine.
Tougher laws are being considered in the UK, New Zealand, South Africa and India.
Many Australian smokers are defiant.
The pictures don't affect me.
I just ignore them.
"You just take a tip and put the box away," says Victor El Hage when buying a cigarette box, on which a photo with a mouth tumor is printed.
Honestly, there's only one reason why I'd stop, and that's my little girl.
James Yu, operator of the tobacco trade "King of the Pack" in downtown Sydney, says the uniform packaging has made it difficult to refill its shelves.
“I used to take an hour to sort a delivery, now I need four,” Yu says.
"The government should have just banned cigarettes completely - then we would have said okay, that's it, we're closing," he added visibly horribly.
In a constantly electrified world, it’s nice to be bored sometimes.
This Thanksgiving I unexpectedly spent five hours at the airport when our plane crashed due to mechanical problems and we had to wait for another plane.
So I had enough time to think a few thoughts about boredom.
I don't want to lie.
Waiting half a day at the airport for a flight is pretty nerve-wracking — even when books, magazines, and iPhones (and of course tax-free shopping) are available.
But more and more academics and child development experts are starting to see boredom as something positive.
When it comes to them, it’s okay for us – and our children – to be bored occasionally.
This forces the brain to lose itself in interesting thought processes, which may promote creativity.
And because most of us are staring at one or the other screen almost constantly these days, the benefits of boredom no longer benefit us.
Should we welcome boredom with open arms?
Oh, yeah.
And no.
I'll come back to that again.
Like many people, I have always assumed that boredom is a relatively current phenomenon that has developed with increasing leisure time.
But Peter Toohey, professor of Greek and Roman history at the University of Calgary in Canada and author of "Boredom: A Lively History" (Yale University Press, 2011), doesn't see it that way.
“In fact, boredom has a very long history,” he says.
The walls of Pompeii adorn a Latin graffiti about boredom that dates back to the first century.
And then there is the question of how we actually define boredom.
According to John D. Eastwood, an associate professor of psychology at the University of York in Ontario, Canada, the problem is that boredom has been defined and discussed in many ways.
After long reading research literature and presenting the idea to a focus group of about 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues concluded that boredom can be defined as the experience of "wanting to do a satisfying job but not being able to do it".
Boring differs from apathy in that the person is not busy, but wants to be.
In apathy, however, there is no urge to do anything.
The key experience of boredom, he says, is a “disruption of the attention process, coupled with bad mood and the feeling that time is just passing slowly.”
Boring can sound almost like depression.
But Professor Eastwood believes that while these two conditions may be related, bored people see the problem in their environment or the world, while depressed people see the problem in themselves.
Sometimes we think we’re bored, even if we’re just having trouble concentrating.
In her study "The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention" - in German for example: "The inactive mind: The definition of boredom in the aspect of attention", which appeared in September in the journal "Perspectives on Psychological Science", Professor Eastwood and his colleagues point to an earlier experiment in which a magisterium listens to a person.
Some groups heard a loud television program from the neighboring room that had nothing to do with the content; others heard it at low volume, so it was barely perceptible, while the third group did not hear these sounds at all.
The people who watched the hard-of-hearing television reported feeling more bored than the other two groups - they had trouble concentrating, couldn't find a reason for it, and attributed their difficulties to boredom.
Trying to focus on a difficult or grueling task can lead to distracting boredom, says Mark J. Fenske, associate professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph in Ontario and one of the authors of the study.
On the other hand, if you perform a monotonous activity - "such as looking for faulty products on a factory conveyor belt, music can distract and help you not to feel bored".
In fact, he says, we now know that ticks and ticks, often interpreted as signs of boredom, can even fight them by keeping people physically more alert.
“Studies have shown that children who are allowed to wander around learn more and retain more information than those who are forced to sit still,” says Professor Fenske.
We all get bored at some point - my late flight, a buzzing speaker, a particularly tiring film.
But some people get bored more easily than others.
To measure these differences, researchers developed a "boring chance scale" in the 1980s.
On the scale, statements like “Many things I have to do are repetitive and monotonous” and “I have so many interests that I don’t have enough time for everything.”
Using such scales, researchers have found that boys are more likely to get bored than girls, according to Stephen Vodanovich, a professor of psychology at the University of West Florida – particularly when it comes to the need for more and a greater variety of external stimuli.
But in general, teenagers are a pretty laid-back bunch.
In 1991, Reed Larson, professor of human and community development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted nearly 400 teenagers and their parents seven to eight times a day with a pager.
He found that 32% of adolescents were bored in school and doing homework, while 23% reported being bored when they were not in school.
However, only 3% of parents reported feeling bored.
Professor Larson says today, 21 years later, he doesn’t know if the percentages have increased or decreased in terms of boredom.
However, he is sure that "youth is perceived as particularly boring", mainly because children and teenagers do not have a great influence on their daily routine.
So back to my original question: Is boredom healthy?
Sometimes not, because in extreme cases, it causes people to take extreme physical risks and lapse into gambling or drugs to relieve them – studies have shown.
On the other hand, many philosophers and authors examine the relationship between boredom and creativity. This opinion is Professor Vodanovich, who has been researching the topic for more than two decades.
“With boredom, the brain wants to tell you that you should do something else,” says Gary Marcus, a professor of psychology at New York University.
But the brain doesn’t always know what to do best.
If you are bored and you use this energy to play guitar and cook, you will be happy.
However, television can provide feelings of happiness in the short term, but in the long term, these become volatile again.
So, if you give your bored child an iPad, it can take it away from boredom, but it has not learned to entertain or control itself, says Professor Fenske.
And he adds: "Self-control transfers from one situation to another."
The child not only learns to converse, but also gains more self-control in other areas.
I don't think we should celebrate boredom.
Nor should we view them too critically.
Instead, our goal should be to feel comfortable even outside of the constant activity and technology entanglement.
Professor Eastwood agrees.
"It sounds like we should be bored more often, but boredom is the tormenting, incessant desire to do something meaningful," he says.
He believes that in truth people are only looking for a way to turn off and relax.
“In an environment where we’re constantly overstimulated, it’s hard to get busy once the noise is muted.”
In Colorado, there is no clear guideline for the new marijuana law
19-year-old community college student and soccer player Anthony Orozco stands in Southeastern Colorado for an offense that will soon be legal in this state: possession of a few marijuana chunks and a pipe with which he smoked them.
According to Orozco, he and some friends were traveling by car in Lamar near the Kansas border on a September day when they were stopped.
After the police officer found marijuana in the car, Orozco was sued for possession of drugs and drug supplies – cavalier crimes, each of which carries a $100 penalty – and received a court order.
"We were treated like criminals," Orozco said.
But is he also one?
In the uncertain weeks following the state’s decision to legalize small amounts of marijuana for personal use, the response to hundreds of smaller drug crimes depends less on the law than on the location.
Hundreds of misdemeanors that revolve around marijuana are already being dropped here and in the state of Washington, which approved similar measures.
The police authorities no longer prosecute adults over the age of 21 for possession to a small extent, which is allowed by law as soon as the new laws come into force in the coming weeks.
But prosecutors in Colorado’s more conservative districts have announced they are continuing to prosecute existing marijuana offenses and are still citing people in court.
At the same time, several cities, from the suburbs of Denver to the Western Mountains, are voting to prevent new, state-licensed marijuana stores from opening in their communities.
“This situation is evolving so fast that I don’t even know what’s going to happen next,” said Daniel J. Oates, Aurora Police Chief, east of Denver.
And regulators in the state of Washington are also scratching their heads.
They are waiting for guidance on setting up a licensing system for the production, manufacture, distribution and sale of the drug - and have a deadline of December 1, 2013.
In Washington, it is believed that Colorado is in any case ahead of most states in regulating marijuana, where the drug was first legalized for medical purposes and then for self-consumption.
“Colorado has a more regulated market, so the state is well-suited for orientation,” said Brian E. Smith, a spokesman for the State of Washington’s liquor regulator.
But Smith also admits that no place or system can do more than serve in the sense of a rough guide.
“We don’t have a real precedent that we can follow,” he adds.
The Washington law, called I-502, comes into force on December 6th, and thus also forms the end point of a gray area in which the state licensing system does not yet exist, but possession is legalized.
And unpleasant practical issues need to be clarified at this time – such as how to agree the state’s requirement of “adequate access” to licensed marijuana with the prohibition of cannabis shops within 300 meters around schools, parks, playgrounds and childcare facilities.
“Nowhere will it be harder to find a licensed cannabis business location than in urban areas, especially in the Seattle metropolitan area,” said Ben Livingston, a spokesman for the Center for Legal Cannabis, a recently formed research group.
On November 21, Chief Oates sent an email to employees in Aurora stating that the attorney general would no longer prosecute minor marijuana offenses in people over the age of 21, and that police would not seek "immediate" criminal charges for those offenses.
Chief Oates added that police would continue to enforce urban regulations to regulate growers of medical marijuana and drug dealers would continue to be prosecuted.
In Weld County in northern Colorado, District Attorney Ken Buck takes a stricter view.
After the vote, he stated that his authority would continue to pursue cases of marijuana possession, mainly to induce consumers to withdraw.
Currently, 119 people have to be held accountable for possession of about 50 grams or less of marijuana in court, although many have been charged with other crimes as well.
"Our authority has a duty to prosecute violations that were crimes at the time of the act," Buck said in a statement.
The reactions are even divisive in places like rural Mesa County, where voters rejected the marijuana initiative.
Police in Grand Junction, the county’s largest city, are no longer showing adults for possession of smaller amounts.
District Attorney Pete Hautzinger supported this decision, but also decided not to drop all pending ownership proceedings.
“I don’t think I’m wasting my time enforcing the law until it changes,” he says.
Although 55% of voters in Colorado supported the measure, it was clear from the outset that it would not be easy to reconcile personal marijuana use with the complexities of government and legal system.
And the conflicting reactions across the state fueled a deep rift among local officials over the big green experiment.
District attorneys are a “cultural barrier,” says Sean McAllister, a Denver-based attorney who represents marijuana offenders in court and acts as a spokesperson for the national organization for marijuana enforcement reform.
“They’ve spent so much of their lives prosecuting people for it that they still can’t accept legalization,” he believes.
As the first states to treat smaller amounts of marijuana such as alcohol, Colorado and Washington are being treated as national pattern cases for the legalization of drugs.
While advocates and state officials are preparing for an era of legal sales, they are also nervously waiting for instructions from the federal government, which wants to continue to treat the sale and cultivation of marijuana at the federal level as a crime.
Proponents of the legalization movement hope that the Ministry of Justice will yield.
Despite several eye-popping arrests of consumers and sellers of medical marijuana, the federal government has largely allowed the sale of medical marijuana in Colorado, Washington and 16 other states.
Kevin A. Sabet, a former drug policy adviser to the Obama administration, believes that while criminal officials are unlikely to enter doors to confiscate smaller amounts of the drugs, they will likely struggle to tolerate legal, state-regulated marijuana deals under the new legislation.
Several cities in Colorado are not even waiting for the federal authorities to act.
Even before Election Day, some local community administrations approved moratoriums on new marijuana businesses, although these could only open in about a year.
Last week, Montrose, a city in the west, passed a six-month ban that is likely to be passed next week.
“We don’t want to get into a position where we license someone and then face a big problem at the federal level,” said Bob Nicholson, a member of the city council.
Our community voted against this amendment.
We judge ourselves by what the community has chosen, not by what the state has chosen.
Many questions are still open.
Petronella Wyatt: I was bullied from Oxford because I am Tory
Not only today’s university students are being attacked for their views
It has always been my biggest dream to get a place at Oxford University.
Both my father and my older brother had attended that university, which I once considered to be the world’s greatest stamp of knowledge, for a modern Greek symposium that promoted the great pillars of civilization – free thinking and tolerance.
But within two weeks of my admission to Worcester College in the late 1980s—where I had intended to study history—I had packed my suitcases again and thus brought about the first scandal of my life.
My father broke down in tears.
My friends were confused.
The Evening Standard said I would have gone because I would have had a problem with co-workers having sex in the next room.
Author A. N. Wilson declared that I had left the university because I was forced to drink from damaged cups.
But the truth was less amusing.
I ran away.
Yes, I did, because I was subjected to systematic bullying and threats.
Not because of my unusual name, or because I came from a private school.
I had been harassed for only one reason - a reason that seemed all the more narrow and cruel in this alleged cradle of enlightenment: my now deceased father Woodrow Wyatt had been an important adviser to Margaret Thatcher and I was a supporter of the Conservative Party.
Why am I mentioning this right now?
Well, according to current reports, a new generation of moderate-rights students is suffering similar persecution.
The organized and rising hatred of Tory students in Oxford has now developed such dimensions that a group of them last week called for the same level of equality protection that benefits gays, disabled people and ethnic minorities.
Conservative members of the Corpus Christi College’s Junior Common Room (JCR) say they are “often actively isolated, personally attacked and declared undesirable” because of their political views.
They are demanding a seat on their college’s equality committee to ensure that their opinions can be freely expressed.
Her situation was exacerbated by a recent documentary about political students on BBC Two, "Wonderland: Young, Bright and on the Right", which portrayed the Tories as eccentric and neo-Nazi.
Among other things, it featured graduate Joe Cooke, former president of the Conservative Student Union of Oxford University, who rode in a Rolls-Royce and wore a silver suit and silver-plated walking stick.
At other universities, conservative students say they are seen as “sinful scapegoats for introducing higher tuition fees.”
The 20-year-old Luke Black, vice president of the Conservative Student Union at the University of Nottingham, said in a Sunday newspaper: “There is a growing left-wing tendency at universities.
“People think we’re like the Bullingdon Club without even getting to know each other.”
Samuel Roberts, 21, and a history student in Corpus Christi who initiated the application for greater protection, is of the opinion that such a climate is "unpleasant". 19-year-old Stephanie Cherill, appointed president of the Conservative Student Association of Oxford says she has observed a growing rejection of students' rights by JCR members.
“This poses a danger to the intellectual discourse and to the well-being of the members,” she says.
In my first few weeks in Oxford, I belonged to such a minority.
As an incredibly shy 18-year-old, I arrived in September 1986.
The hatred of the Conservative Party had reached its peak.
Last year, the university voted not to award Margaret Thatcher, a former student, an honorary degree due to cuts in higher education.
The atmosphere would have even alarmed Stalinists.
In the first days of the first semester week, when new students got to know each other and the tutors, I got a taste of what would happen in the future.
I experienced that the tutors not only tolerated the mockery of Tory students, but even participated with joy in it.
Political issues such as the miners’ strike, privatization and the government’s rejection of sanctions against South Africa’s apartheid regime found their way into the wood-paneled rooms of the tutorial.
At my first of these events I was supposed to translate French texts from the 18th century into English. I had not been prepared for what was to come next.
"Miss Wyatt," said tutor Harry Pitt (now deceased), "please translate the first paragraph."
I tripped on it.
Pitt was a small man with a cake dough-like face, and quite polite.
“Are Thatcher supporters refusing to learn French, or are they just stupid?” he asked me.
The other students nodded.
There were tears in my eyes.
"I suggest they take a few French lessons in your spare time - so if you're not too busy with your social activities," Pitt growled at me.
I returned to my room with my head hanging back.
That night I was sitting in college alone at dinner when someone lightly tapped me on the shoulder.
It was a second-year English student named James who introduced himself as a member of the Conservative Student Union.
“I know who you are,” he said kindly.
Unfortunately, it's the way it is.
Anyone suspected of being Tory is being harassed.
It's bad enough for me, but they know your father Margaret Thatcher is close, so it's going to be worse for you.
Most Tory freshmen pretend to be supporters of the Labour Party.
In a local pub, I later tried to adjust.
I insisted that I did not agree with Mrs Thatcher on all points.
This trick should prove unsuccessful.
A student in philosophy, politics, and economics who had ironically attended the conservative Eton College said to me, “You are the daughter of a fascist pig.”
You're dirty.
Other students shared their opinions.
I was perverted and dirty.
"How do Tories have sex?" one asked me.
They're fighting each other, aren't they?
I felt like homosexuals must have felt before the more liberal legislation of the United States.
Would I ever be able to live a normal life at Oxford University?
Would I be able to meet like-minded people only after dark?
Should I turn to the Labour Party and suppress my natural inclinations?
The three years that were before me stretched before my spiritual eye into a purgatory of self-denial and isolation.
The only tutor who openly identified himself as Tory was Norman Stone, professor of contemporary history, who was based in my college.
He was hated not only for being a conservative, but also because he had advised Thatcher on foreign policy and written speeches for her.
He was rarely there.
He hated the place, found it provincial and petty, and rejected it for its Marxist-Determinist historical perspective.
In 1997 he took up a professorship at Bilkent University in Ankara, Turkey.
“You won’t be happy here,” he told me.
I began to commute between Oxford and my parents’ house and found refuge with more open-minded friends and family members in the city.
I told my father that I hated Oxford and why I did it.
He seemed incredulous.
During his time in the 1940s, all political views were accepted.
“But it’s the best place in the world,” he said softly.
They would never do such a thing, not in my city of dreaming tower peaks.
Even my communist friends have always shown impeccable manners.
His wet eyes were dizzy.
Give the whole thing a chance.
I'm sure you're just being teased.
It would break my heart if you left.
Exhausted by my frequent trips to London, my emotional resistance became weaker.
One of my male friends, also Tory supporters, had given in to the pressure and disavowed his beliefs.
During a tutorial the following week, in which another storyteller had seriously claimed that I was “an enemy of the people,” I decided to do the same.
Even though I secretly fell out of shame, I admitted that my parents had subjected me to a “brainwashing” and called them “old bastards.”
The relief only lasted a short time.
It was my father who struck the last nail in the coffin of my Oxford career.
At that time, he wrote two columns a week in the Murdoch Press.
My door was locked.
I hid in my room, and after five minutes my bunnies gave up.
When they left, I packed a suitcase and took the first train to London.
I never came back.
You can call me a whiny slut.
But no 18-year-old should ever have to suffer such intimidation and malice in an educational institution.
And even more tragic is that it was Oxford - a university that not only produced 14 Tory prime ministers, but still hides behind an undeserved reputation for equality and freedom of thought.
