The most difficult profession in the world: the human work animals of Kawah Ijen
For four euros, the carriers of the Indonesian volcano risk their lives and their health when they carry 70 kilos of sulfur over the steep, rocky paths.
There are people for whom their work is hell, and others literally work in hell.
This is the case with Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who earn their living by extracting sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano in the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
To do this, it has to descend every day to the bottom of its crater, where the sulfur-containing gas flowing out of the earth solidifies in contact with the air.
After breaking out large sulfur stones that can weigh a total of up to 70 kilograms, he transports them in two bamboo baskets on his shoulders over the sloping stone paths.
Although it is only 250 meters to the top of the volcano, which rises to a height of 2,386 meters, but the exhausted carriers need more than 40 minutes for the ascent at turtle pace, maintaining balance and carefully setting their steps so that they do not slip and crash.
