After the U.S. Court of Appeals upheld a ruling that does not recognize the restructuring of Vitro Group’s liabilities that was achieved through a trade bankruptcy in Mexico, an ominous precedent is created for any national company with branches in the neighboring country that has payment problems.
So one could say that the procedures for the survival of the companies that allow Mexican laws have no validity in the country of the stars and stripes in contradiction to international agreements.
In practice, the recognition of the judgment by Judge Harlin Hale in the Bancarrotas District Court for the Northern District of Texas on June 15 results in the Mexican companies being helpless in the confiscation of their property beyond the River Bravo.
However, the decision opens the door for Mexico’s largest glassmaker to appeal to the United States Supreme Court over three inconsistencies.
While the judge of the case points out that the creditors must be subject to the bankruptcy law of the United States, the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals, based in New Orleans, first says that the main proceedings concern the commercial bankruptcy dealt with in Mexico.
The first point would mean that international cooperation in insolvency proceedings of companies with a cross-border profile is not known.
In fact, for this purpose, the United Nations Model Law for the Unification of International Trade Law was created, with the American Law Institute being used as a conciliator.
Secondly, the judgment provides that, without the votes of the companies, the necessary majority for the restructuring of the liabilities would not have been reached after the recognition of the liabilities in the bankruptcy estate held by the Vitro branches with their parent company.
However, this possibility is recognized by the Mexican laws.
In fact, Vitro is not the first case where this scheme was approved.
There are half a dozen examples, including Agrimex and Comercial Mexicana, whose liabilities have been confirmed among companies in the group by the Instituto Federal de Concursos Mercantiles (Federal Institute of Commercial Bankruptcy).
