The serious thing about this case is that the Court set aside a document sent by the Government of Mexico under the figura amicus curiae (Friend of the Court), which describes the procedure carried out by Vitro under the Trade Bankruptcy Act, and which points out that it had been signed into law strictly to the Chapters of the 15 Agreement signed by the two countries.
In addition, it is noted that the country has submitted to the principles of the United Nations Commission on International Trade, i.e. the established rules for cases of cross-border insolvency that guarantee equality of debtors and creditors.
