Héctor "Hetin" Reyes: "Basketball was my life"
The basketball world champion, Héctor "Hetin" Reyes, has been involved in basket sports for more than 60 years and has traveled the world.
Few in Puerto Rico have such a large intellectual collection of the history of the country's basketball as Héctor "Hetin" Reyes.
Before being tied to the wheelchair by a stroke in 2008, Rexes was part of the sport for 6 years, whether it was as a lower-class player, a player of the first national league, a proxy and a leader in the BSN with the Vaqueros de Bayam<0xC3><0xB3>n or president of the Basketball Association.
"Throughout my life, I have put on many hats in basketball, even several at the same time, when I was president of the BSN, chief executive of the national team and president of the association in the 90s," Reyes recalled during a visit to Primera Hora's home in Bayam<0xC3><0xB3>n, where he lives with Isabel, his faithful wife for more than 50 years.
“Basketball was my life.”
Reyes does not exaggerate with this statement.
The walls of his house are almost all decorated with photos and memories of his long career and testify to them.
Bayam<0xC3><0xB3>n in the heart
The most emotional memories are those of his time with the Vaqueros from the mid-50s as a player until 1982, when he celebrated his 15th anniversary as co-manager or managing director of the club.
“These were my best years I’ve enjoyed the most, because I’ve been part of eight championships of the Vaqueros since 1967, whether as managing director, co-manager or coach.
There were many fulfilling years, including the five consecutive championships from 1971 to 1975.
And then I said goodbye to a championship in 1981, the year of Jerome Mincy’s debut at BSN.
From then on, "Cuco" took over Ortiz, who was a very good manager," Reyes says.
I remember Gene Bartow, who worked here as a coach and was employed at the University of Alabama (Birmingham), saying to me, “I have a very strong and 2 m tall player.
