Larry Hagman is dead.
Larry Hagman was born on September 21, 1931 in Forth Worth, Texas, and became world famous with his role as John Ross Ewing, better known as "J.R." in the television series "Dallas", where he played an unscrupulous, insidious and manipulative businessman.
Larry Hagman, whose role as oil magnate J.R. Ewing in the television series "Dallas" became a symbol of the greed of the 80s, is dead.
He was 81 years old.
Hagman, who returned this year as J.R. in a new season of “Dallas,” died Friday afternoon of cancer complications, according to a family press release to The Associated Press by Warner Bros., producer of “Dallas.”
"Larry was back in his beloved hometown of Dallas, where he once again played the iconic role he liked the most," the family said.
Larry’s family and his closest friends were with him in Dallas for the Thanksgiving celebrations.
Linda Gray, who played his wife in the original and sequel series, was with Hagman when he died in Dallas hospital, her publicist Jeffrey Lane said.
He made everyone who knew him happy.
He was creative, generous, funny, funny, loving and talented, and I will miss him very much.
“He was an original person and lived life to the fullest,” Gray said in a statement.
Hagman was diagnosed with cirrhosis of the liver in 1992, and he admitted to drinking heavily for years.
In 1995, a malignant tumor was found in his liver, and he underwent a transplant.
In the years before "Dallas", Hagman became known on television as a nice guy in the years 1965 to 1970 with the sitcom "Charming Jeannie" of the NBC television station.
There, he played the astronaut Tony Nelson, whose life is turned upside down when he meets an attractive "Jinn" (played by Barbara Eden) who will live with him at home.
He also starred in two short-lived comedies, The Good Life (NBC, 1971–72) and Here We Go Again (ABC, 1973).
His film works included critically acclaimed roles in "The Group", "Harry and Tonto" and "Primary Colors".
But it was his masterful interpretation of the charmingly despicable J.R. that made Hagman a superstar.
The CBS drama series about the Ewing clan and other characters in their environment was broadcast from April 1978 to May 1991.
The slogan "Who shot J.R.", which was supposed to create the expectation for an episode full of emotions, where the character of Hagmann was almost killed, led to international speculation, and millions of dollars were bet in betting houses.
The series reached a record number of viewers at the time.
When the answer was revealed in a chapter in November 1990, it was seen by an average of 41 million viewers turning "Dallas" into the second most viewed entertainment program since the end of "MASH" in 1983, which had 50 million viewers.
It was Kristin, the sister-in-law of J.R. (played by Mary Crosby) who had shot.
J.R. had impregnated her and threatened to portray her as a prostitute if she did not leave the city, but others also had reasons to want to see him dead.
Hagman interpreted the role of Ewing as a corrupt, insatiable man with a charismatic smile: a sly businessman and unfaithful husband who sought to have his alcoholic wife Sue Ellen (Linda Gray) inducted.
“I know what to put on J.R.’s tombstone,” Hagman said in 1988.
It should be called "Here rests the honorable citizen J.R. Ewing".
This is the only deal he didn't win.
Victoria Principal, co-star of the original series, recalled Hagman on Friday as a "huge personality on and off the screen".
It is unforgettable and irreplaceable for millions of worshippers in the world, and it remains in our hearts to those who have been lucky enough to know and love it.
Ten episodes of the new edition of "Dallas" were broadcast a few months ago with great success on the TNT television channel.
The recording of five chapters for the second season was completed, and a sixth chapter was just filmed, the broadcaster informed.
There was no immediate explanation from Warner or TNT as to how the loss of Hagmann would be dealt with in the series.
Born in Fort Worth, Texas, he was the son of actress and singer Mary Martin, who played classic works such as "South Pacific" and "Peter Pan".
