Start of the course that studies the "End of the World"
Each week, students explore apocalyptic topics such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
Every semester, when the religious professor decided to take a course on the end of the world, he knew he had an irresistible fishing hook: the end of the Mayan calendar’s “long countdown” on December 21, which many people believed meant the end of the world.
But Charmé had no idea what to expect in the following two months: the destructive Hurricane Sandy, which some have called “Deudarmagedon,” as well as a growing conflict involving Israel, the place from which Christian theorists believe the apocalypse begins.
“I didn’t realize this was going to be the most apocalyptic semester there has ever been,” Charmé told students at Rutgers-Camden University in New Jersey this week.
If someone analyzes what has happened in the world today as if we were thirty days away from it, this would be a really good period.
And he reminds us that the bad is good for those with an apocalyptic mentality.
And he’s not the only professor to offer courses on the “end of the world” this semester, which should actually be the last in history.
In Temple, Assistant Professor Barry Vacker gives the course "Media, Culture and the End of the World."
Each week, students explore apocalyptic topics such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
“We analyze why these ideas spread over time,” he said, as well as the way hypothetical scenarios are offered that lead to a particular human behavior.
If nuclear material gets into the hands of terrorists, for example, a war could break out.
This month, the students analyzed films with apocalyptic content and examined how they could be compared to real life.
“I have tried to inform students about what is possible, likely, believable and impossible,” Vacker said.
On the main campus of the University of Pennsylvania, Latin American History Professor Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, a visiting professor of art history and anthropology, have formed a team to offer a course with the simple designation “The End of the World.”
"We are not taking up in 2012 so that we always retain the option of being able to hold the course again in case the world does not go down," Restall said.
Despite the "precedented demise", students must study, create projects and take part in final exams.
In Penn State, the final exam is conducted on the eve of the apocalypse, which is why students have no other chance than "to continue working into the night, where the world is supposedly ending," Restall said.
The courses were very popular.
"In two hours there were no more places," Restall said of his course for high-average students, which filled with 35 students.
For weeks before the start of the semester, we received emails from students asking if there were still places available.
The students, for their part, assure that the course is one of the most interesting.
“It’s fascinating to see what people are doing to comfort themselves,” said Bridgid Robinson, a 23-year-old student at Rutgers Camden for Religion and Sociology from Haddonfield, New Jersey.
The apocalyptic cult or religious mentality is actually just a matter of comfort or lack thereof.
Will Wekesa, a 25-year-old psychology and nursing student, says he has seen all the apocalyptic movies.
“I’ve never heard of a class where this is taught,” he said.
I'm enjoying it.
But none of the students surveyed — let alone a professor — said they believed in the last date of December 21.
“Our first project dealt with the Mayan prophecy, and in some ways we discredit it,” said Julie Zeglen, a student last year at Temple, 21 years old and from West Chester.
The Mayans never predicted the end of the world; it’s just a key point in the calendar, Restall said.
He notes, however, that in Western society there is an apocalyptic fear that dates back several centuries when people reacted to changes in their environment with the prediction of the end of the world.
The Internet has increased these speculations.
“Other places, people don’t think that way,” he says.
This is mainly the case in the English-speaking world.
Joseph Dougherty, a religious professor at La Salle University who teaches in the Philippines this year, quickly answers the question of whether he would know a course there about the “end of the world”.
“The Philippines does not participate in the end of the world,” he wrote as an indication of an exception by a higher authority.
We have a pardon from the Pope.
Restall pointed out that over the years many days were spoken of by the last court, and said that if nothing happens on December 21, "people immediately think of a new date" or philosophize that December 21 is the beginning of a seven-year period after which the world would end.
Students and professors take this date lightly.
Several said they wanted to go to celebrations about "the end of the world".
“Maybe I’ll call a few friends so we can laugh together,” said Samira Ford, a 20-year-old communications student.
